No Liberating Novel for Tymoshenko by Parliament
The Ukrainian parliament today rejected the request to abolish the paragraphs on the basis of which opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko had been convicted as part of a draft of the Criminal Code.
The new regulation, which could have paved the way for the release of the imprisoned Prime Minister, was rejected by MPs at the second reading of the request for the easing of penalties for economic offences.
Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison in October for concluding an allegedly unfavorable contract with Russia for the purchase of natural gas.
The verdict is not yet legally valid, in December the appeal of the convicts is to be heard in court.
Timoshenko himself refers to the verdict as a political revenge of the regime and also in the West, the trial raised the suspicion of bias of the court.
The request, paragraph 365, on the basis of which the Prime Minister was sentenced to be removed from the Criminal Code, was supported by 147 MPs.
226 votes would have been required for its adoption.
