The menu of a fatty child: It does not eat breakfast and eats for dinner sausage
More than a third of children from 9 to 13 have problems with obesity, with 9 percent of all students and 5 percent of all children being overweight.
Recent surveys have shown that obese children mostly come from families with unhealthy lifestyles.
This shows once again how important for a person’s healthy development is the environment in which he grows up and the examples that surround him.
On the tables of obese children, sausages are up to half as often on the table as in families where normal-weight children live.
More than 19 percent of overweight children had an evening meal on the eve of the education campaign under the motto "Obesity is not a coincidence".
In families with toddlers, sport is not one of the favorite occupations, but the majority of today’s students also do – only 15 percent answered that their parents find time for active exercise at least once a week.
Survey of 900 children
The survey took place last year at the end of the school year, with almost 900 children from primary schools across the Czech Republic surveyed.
This was already the second year of the "Adiposity is not a coincidence" campaign, which is supported by the General Health Insurance Fund and the Unilever company.
So far, more than 12 thousand students from 4th and 8th grade participated in the project.
Unhealthy diet and lack of exercise in the family are crucial factors responsible for the alarming increase in the number of children with overweight or even obesity.
"For example, only half of the children surveyed led, five times a day, to eat breakfast-second breakfast-lunch-vesper-evening bread mode - one of the main prerequisites for a healthy diet," said one of the survey results.
No breakfast and sausage for dinner
Experts point out that relative small things, such as the family’s regular breakfast time, are also important for a child’s healthy development.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23 percent of students’ families eat breakfast.
And in most families, everyone eats breakfast on their own.
Worst of all was the finding that in every tenth family there is no breakfast at all.
Breakfast is considered the cornerstone of a healthy daily diet.
The survey test showed, among other things, that in the families of overweight children, unhealthy apples are consumed much more often.
And almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sweet lemonades every day (70 percent)
Although more than 40 percent of the children surveyed do sports, only less than half of their parents do - namely only 15 percent.
Create your own menu
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to come up with their own meal plan based on their appetite and opinion.
“What Czech children between the ages of 12 and 15 prefer in terms of nutrition is far from the ideal of a healthy diet.
Among their favorite dishes were many flour dishes, meat dishes and, of course, sweets.
"Apprehensive is above all the great popularity of sweet lemonades," the final report on this survey emphasizes.
At lunch, i.e. the main course, pastries beat just before poultry.
The children almost did not like legumes and also the popularity of fish and vegetable dishes as lunch was very low.
Return to Health
At the same time, the survey also showed that children are quite willing to change their eating habits if they get the right information.
"In the control group of respondents who filled out the questionnaire after the conclusion of the enlightening lecture "Obesity is not a coincidence", in many cases there was a significant shift in preferences towards principles of healthy eating," the results of the project stated.
This was evident, for example, in the sweet limos, where many children began to give priority to ordinary water.
In the questionnaire, the children also crossed poultry or fish much more often as the main dish of the day and were ready to eat less dumplings or sweet foods.
