V Need for Speed: "The Run" - the illegal race across America
Rezension
The originally carefree ride is made by a series of completely avoidable, amateurish mistakes to the routine ride to the early layer.
While the ambitions were largely met, what good is it if obviously no one wanted to do a little more?
Even before he came to the store, the new part with the subtitle "The Run" aroused high expectations.
After all, he promised to move the game series "Need for Speed" back into a new dimension and in the playable demonstration examples, he didn't actually seem to be just one of many action racing games.
We were also curious as to how the fitted passages turn out, in which the main protagonist gets out of the car and continues on foot.
But as you are used to with NFS, in the end, much is different than you expected.
Sure - potentially they are quite decent arcade races, but overall, the game is tempered by some superfluous mistakes that have been present in this series for more or less a few years.
So these are actually no longer mistakes, but rather signs of a basically incomprehensible laziness of the game developers.
The adventure starts very well.
First introduced to history, whose main character Jack has certain problems of a personal nature; the only solution seems to be to participate in an illegal race across America.
In San Francisco, that is, on the west coast, you sit on the steering wheel - with the task of being the first in New York.
The basic idea includes a number of interesting elements.
The entire route is divided into ten stages and more than fifty individual races.
This means that each race is held on a different track and that the individual stages take place in a different, sufficiently different and interesting environment.
You don’t get the impression that the game would always offer the same thing.
Some environments are still very nice to look at, although the technical level of the graphics does not exceed that of the previous parts of the series.
So nothing world-moving.
But the journey through the desert, through the autumn landscape or up through the deep snowy landscape seems very visually pleasant.
From time to time, unusual elements bring a bit of variety to the individual races.
In the desert, for example, one is surprised by a desert storm, which severely limits the view.
In the mountains, in turn, one must be hellishly careful that one is not spilled by an avalanche.
In addition, the individual races are installed quite well in a row.
Only a few, but they are enough.
For a while you try to overcome the prescribed number of opponents (in principle a classic race), then you have time to catch up (classical race against the stopwatch), then you expect another personal duel with a single opponent.
And that includes the police, who want to mess up the whole thing.
A novelty are passages in which Jack leaves the car.
This is more about certain interactive animations, in which Jack flees from someone and where the player has to help him by pressing the right button at the right moment.
So nothing complicated.
It is surprising, however, that there are far fewer such passages in the game than one would expect (in particular, probably only three).
Ultimately, this is more to the advantage, because this element at least has no chance to get boring - it belongs in the context of the above, among the elements that make the game more varied.
The driving model moves in the footsteps of the previous parts.
That is, from today's point of view, although it does not tear down trees, on the other hand, one could not claim that it would be bad.
If you are looking for realistic simulations, you need to look elsewhere.
But for an action-packed race, the local driving model will continue to do well, although you could find better in the competition.
Until then, everything is in perfect order.
Real problems do not appear until after a certain time.
In contrast to the driving model, the collision model is not quite OK.
From a game of this kind is hardly to be expected that it calculates complicated deformations and collisions, but if you practically have no idea before any impact on any object, how the car behaves, then obviously everything is not okay.
Typical example: When passing or overtaking approaching cars, in some places you "strip" the other car only slightly, but in other, almost identical situation, you get into the swing and turn wild pirouettes.
Or drive the car straight to junk.
Thanks to the restart system, this does not matter anymore, it is always annoying.
The restarts are resolved as follows: if you have total damage or land far away from the track, then you throw the game back to the last point of the track.
Only - in each race you have only five restarts.
When you have exhausted them, everything starts from the front.
So the restarts are more like a tool, in case something fails, but you should not rely on them.
But sometimes restarting doesn’t even help, because nothing else helps but to learn the critical section from the head.
It’s a shame that the same things often happen in the same place.
For example, you have to go through some curves in a very specific way, otherwise you simply do not fit through.
Elsewhere, “civil” cars are always in the same configuration, whether you arrive first or fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is especially annoying in situations when you see that the opponent passes two cars in front of you, but until you get there yourself, the cars are already in such a position that you have to bypass or brake them.
And it doesn’t matter when you get there, because everything is designed in such a way that it always comes close to your nose.
The contractors have other advantages.
Throughout the game there are a few places where you are always overtaken by the same opponent in the same place and again here regardless of the time.
The craziest thing is to finish the game on the long bridge, which you pass in the opposite direction.
The opponent must obviously overtake someone here to get the hell out of here.
And if he is already in front of you, then of course he takes a look at you, so that at first you drive your own car there a few times in Klump.
Of course - you just want to make the game more exciting and exciting, but this intention is so clear that it quickly loses the joy of the game.
And that’s a shame, because despite the simpler driving model, the game is overall quite entertaining and sometimes so action-packed that you almost no longer know where one’s head is.
And in principle, it doesn't matter what "guilt" is - the concept with fifty unique routes, the arrangement of the races in a way that no boredom can arise, or something completely different...
An unusual idea is also the change of car in the course of the races.
You should not overlook the gas stations on the route, because it is here that you can change the car, although in most cases the car you just have is enough.
The cars are divided into three categories.
The sports cars are well suited for urban areas, the strong American limousines for straight highways and exotic super sports cars for technical trips, for example on the serpentines in the mountains.
Hand in hand with the mode of the game story also goes the task mode (challenges) - that is, the races in the individual localities that you know from the story.
Here there are not only medals, but also experience points for your own profile, which is common for the tasks (challenges) and the story.
To reach the higher driver level, various items need to be unlocked: from the car to the backgrounds for the profile.
This is at the same time connected with the online function Autolog, which compares its own results with those of other players and also provides further collective functions.
One of the other incomprehensible carvers is a situation in the last race of history.
Here you can get by car into a subway tunnel (myways), where you can ride on the rails for a long time in the dark (myways).
On the tacho, numbers look between 150 and 200 km/h (myself), but then suddenly a subway comes from behind and drives an uncompromising to scrap.
In our editorial staff we will probably argue for a long time whether this was a blackout of the game designers or whether the authors think we are so stupid.
The technical side is nothing overwhelming but at least the visual overall impression is in most cases quite appealing and here and there even brilliant.
It is all the more annoying that at some exciting moments the image repetition frequency slows down and sometimes this is quite dramatic.
However, this applies in particular to accidents with a larger number of participants, where a continuous FPS is of no use at all.
The sound is as far as OK and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to appeal to as wide a range as possible rather young audiences, a soundtrack was created a l<0xC3><0xA1> "from everyone something" - but who buys such a game already because of the music?!
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run? The feelings are more mixed.
If the game hadn’t been tempered by the aforementioned totally unnecessary mistakes, we could have argued with the chest tone of conviction that The Run is the best piece of NFS in recent years.
But somehow the game seems unfinished.
A great pleasure in itself, but one should be prepared to face these mistakes with the power of airport headlights.
