Brand Story:
Innovator IBM enters the second century of its existence
If you wanted to search for a suitable word that most accurately characterizes IBM’s strategy, then this would probably be the word “longitudinal”.
For the general public, IBM is synonymous with the technological revolution, known as a modern company, although a century has passed since its foundation.
The basis for this longevity was laid by her first boss - the visionary Thomas J. Watson sen.
Already he represented the slogan, countless worldwide problems could easily be solved if people were willing to think a little.
His slogan "Think!" became the trademark for the life of the future giant (and at the same time the title of the company's internal magazine, which began to be published at IBM as early as 1935).
This was also the basis of Watsen’s thoroughly prepared corporate culture.
“For us at IBM, this long-term thinking means a continuous movement towards the future.
IBM survived and was successful for a whole century because it remained true to its principles and did not shy away from changing everything else around it.
This allowed us to transform the technologies, the business and also the society over the course of our first century.
We hope to do even more in the next hundred years,” said Samuel J. Palmisano, the company’s current director on the occasion of the anniversary.
A well-thought-out system
Watson already operated his employees’ social care in the thirties – in a similar way to the entrepreneur Ba<0xC5><0xA5>a in Czechoslovakia: the IBM people had paid holidays as one of the first American employees, an insurance by the entrepreneur plus elegant uniforms as workwear and a well-thought-out system of remuneration for the best newcomers and herders.
IBM’s long-term relationships with its customers are equally sophisticated.
From the beginning, the company was brilliant in talent promotion - as one of the first companies in the world, IBM lifted any discrimination - and was able to choose accordingly.
In line with this anti-discrimination strategy is also the current plan, which Palmisan will be replaced at the head of IBM next year by a woman - Virginia Rometty.
She has been with IBM for 30 years and has previously held the position of Head of Sales, Marketing and Strategy.
IBM has been making so-called online brainstorming in recent years, from which many future strategies and innovations are emerging.
No wonder - there are enough ideas, after all, almost half a million people are employed in the company.
An institution with a good reputation
Their unwavering position in the business guarantees the company a strong image, both inside and outside.
"From the beginning, IBM had the concept of an institution rather than a mere technology company," said Harvard Business School professor and author of a book about IBM, Rosabeth Moss Kanter.
“IBM is not a technology company, but a company that helps solve business problems using technologies,” added George Colony of consulting firm Forrester Research.
As the company itself emphasizes, it is a difference to be only present in the market or to directly shape it through this presence.
IBM – in the states of its logo called “Big Blue” because of its familiarity, has grown into one of the largest companies in the world in a century.
It’s one of the most versatile technology companies ever – IBM develops hardware and software, infrastructure, hosting and consulting services across an incredible range of products – from servers to nanotechnology.
Of all American technology companies, IBM owns the most patents and already five of its employees have been awarded the Nobel Prize.
His most well-known inventions include e.g. ATM machines, credit cards, financial swaps, barcodes or the floppy disk.
With a market capitalization of about $220 billion, IBM was the second-largest technology company this year (similar to Apple), surpassing Microsoft for the first time since 1996.
The look ahead
Not all products and innovations met the taste of today's customers - for example, unhappy were the attempt with their own operating system OS/2, the online service Prodigy or even the computer IBM PC Jr.
“Business is based on the forward movement, so you can’t tie yourself emotionally to the past,” says Samuel J. Palmisano.
That’s why IBM has no problem building its foundation walls on different platforms — and if they don’t work, leave them again.
In contrast to the opponent Microsoft, which in principle stands and falls with its Windows operating system.
Promising technologies
Services, software and hardware account for one-fifth of IBM’s profits.
In 1990, hardware with a share of more than fifty percent was the most represented.
Since 2000, IBM has sold $15 billion worth of low-yielding assets, but at the same time, it has invested $58 billion in the purchase of future-proof technologies.
In these investments, IBM continues after 2008, when the modern financial crisis swept the world like a storm for the first time.
Here, too, IBM remained true to the legacy of its first boss, Thomas J. Watson, who increased its investment in the midst of the great global economic crisis.
So far, it seems that the company IBM survives the current crisis intact.
The value of IBM’s shares has rocketed by 120 percent since 2008, and the company’s net income is growing continuously.
IBM’s corporate slogan is: Everything can be changed – only the values can’t.
That is why it can be expected that this flexible giant will also overcome the next crisis.
IBM Story: From Cheese Cutter to Spaceflight
IBM (International Business Machines), founded in New York a hundred years ago, initially had a rather complicated name – Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was not adopted until 1924 - originally it was a brand name for a branch in Canada and South America.
The foundation of the later IBM company was laid by the merger of four companies, whose history goes back to the 80s of the 19th century.
They had technologies, such as the famous card clocks for registering the start and end of work.
The architect of this new company was Charles Ranlett Flint, who also held the chairmanship of the Supervisory Board until 1930.
And it was Flint who hired the head of the rival Thomas J. Watson to help him run the company.
This leader then even put the founders of IBM in the shadows - Watson's ideas are still based on the invincible culture and identity of the company.
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name suggests, began manufacturing and selling all kinds of machines for trade – from sausage and cheese cutters to cash registers.
In the first four decades that Watson led the company, he doubled its revenues to nine million dollars and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that he sat in the executive chair for forty years, only then was he replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began to work on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, engineers and computers at NASA's IBM helped direct flights into space - to Mercury and Saturn, and in 1969 also the famous flight of man to the moon.
In 1964, IBM developed the first computer family with the same computer architecture – the IBM System/360 series.
A classic PC that set the computer standard of the time came on the market in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but on the other hand, it bought the consulting part of the company PricewaterhouseCoopers and thereby fully entered the business of consulting services and services with high added value.
The strategy that IBM has been paying off over the last three years is the concept of “Smarter Planet”.
It embodies the intention to use technologies in a smart way in areas that have not yet been planned, e.g. also to improve the situation in traffic and in city administration.
In the commercial sector, IBM recently introduced the “Smart Commerce” platform, which is designed to help traders manage the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in the Czech Republic.
As early as 1932, IBM established a branch in what was then Czechoslovakia – the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM <0xC4><0x8C>R also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe is based in Prague and there is also a world-class research team dealing with the technology of voice recognition.
