Development of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five approved state travel agencies in the then <0xC4><0x8C>SSR: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
The travel agencies at that time mainly sold only trips to the socialist Eastern bloc countries, in the West only selected ones were allowed at that time.
And so Czech tourists traveled to the Baltic Sea (to the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sotschi on the Crimean peninsula on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary to the Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when one was also allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia struck a pro-Western course and therefore travel to Yugoslavia was severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that not even citizens of the Eastern Bloc (i.e. the Czechoslovaks) were allowed to travel freely within the framework of the socialist countries.
For example, if a citizen of the USSR wanted to travel to Poland individually or even to the Soviet Union, then he needed an invitation letter, otherwise individual trips were not possible.
Even then, the travel agencies also offered trips to the West, but then you had to buy huge snakes or even stay in your sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
The matter had not gone on for a long time.
The so-called currency requirement - the condition for a trip to the West - was only granted to "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so without currency usage it would have been impossible to raise the necessary funds (Western currency) for a trip to the West.
Therefore, the vast majority of Czechs spent their holidays in the Czech Republic, no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and datschen - a habit that continues to this day.
The Velvet Revolution of 1989 was followed by a travel revolution of the Czechs.
While until 1989 a holiday in the GDR or in Bulgaria was the measure of all things, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their foreign holidays in countries all over the world.
A huge paradox, of which you are not even aware today, is the fact that you could not travel to the currently most popular holiday country of the Czech Republic - Croatia until 1989 at all, because it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
Right from the beginning of the 90s of the last century, foreign exchange duty was abolished in the neighboring Western European countries, which resulted in a huge wave of short visits, especially to Vienna in Austria and to Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not get enough of their trips to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to have been there for at least a few days.
So the Czech holidaymakers slept in the park on trips to Paris in the tent, because who would have had the money for an accommodation in a hotel or in a pension at that time.
A typical feature when travelling abroad from the Czech Republic at that time was a luggage room packed with canned goods, beer and permanent sausage, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech crown - after decades, our tourists were finally able to buy the Western currency freely.
Our standard of living and thus the average wages also increased, which led to another important moment in 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, travel agencies began to regularly prepare travel by charter flights after 1997, which made air travel incredibly affordable compared to the past thanks to the ability to negotiate volume discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czech Republic, with the exception of the United States, had already had foreign exchange-free payment transactions with all the highly developed countries of the world, which made travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of “post-salt” travel came in 2000 when, thanks to the high demand, the first direct charter flight to an exotic country – to Thailand – was completed.
Since then, every year, direct charter flights with Czech passengers fly to distant sunny countries; this year, twelve exotic destinations are flown directly from the Czech Republic.
The 100 thousand Czechs travel to exotic countries every year!
Another significant moment in the epoch that marked our “post-revolutionary” development came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most highly developed countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs spent for the first time more than half of their holiday abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history spent more than 15 thousand CZK per head for a single holiday stay including the cost of the holiday resort.
