Planschpool in UFO-Optik, Prunkpools in Budapest: Those who travel through Europe can experience its blue wonder - and after a city tour or a hike rest the tired legs in bubble baths.
A book shows where wellness in the water is most beautiful.
When Iris Meder went on a research trip in the past one and a half years, one thing was not to be missed in her luggage: her swimsuit.
Lying back on the water, she gazed up at artfully designed domes, she met swam marble puddles waiting for her at the edge of the pool, and marveled at meticulously restored Art Nouveau swimming pools.
If she liked a bath, she took it in flight in her notebook - along with interesting details about the construction and history of the building.
More than 200 swimming pools were explored in this way by architectural historian Meder - and she now presents them in her recently published book "Badefreiden": Volksswimmhallen in Munich, historic bathing palaces in the Black Forest, "hardcore concrete buildings" in the Taunus.
Through 13 countries, she led her "trip to the most extraordinary baths in Central Europe": In addition to Germany, Austria and Switzerland, she visited places in Italy, France, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Slovenia, Hungary, Romania, Poland - and one city each in Luxembourg, Serbia and Croatia.
The 46-year-old German is a true bathing culture enthusiast.
With sports, she does not have much on her mind, says Meder - only in the water it is different.
It’s just annoying that swimming fans have to settle down with blue tiles and chlorine, while joggers can breathe in the bewitching scent of spruce forests or listen to cheerful bird whispers in the park.
“One day I wondered why swimming pools must always be so ugly,” says the Vienna-based meder.
"So I started to collect beautiful baths."
Water surface doubles architecture
Plaster in the spring pool and essential sauna oils - the wellness factor in bathrooms is so great because all the senses are served, according to Meder.
And if the builders have put in the effort, swimming pools can be a real treat: "Instead of a floor, you have a water surface in bathrooms."
"It is transparent on the one hand, but on the other it reflects the beauty of the whole building."
Everything doubles visually: high vaults, colorful tiles, springboards.
The small-format picture book "Badefreuden" provides 190 pages of information about the architectural and cultural history of historical wellness oases - but above all, it makes you want to jump into the blue.
Remarkable specimens were discovered by pool collector Meder during her research in Hungary.
In addition to magnificent healing baths such as the 100-year-old Széchenyi bath in Budapest, she found a nitrate-containing water in an ancient karst cave (cave bath in Miskolc-Tapolca) as well as a thermal bath, whose basins are filled with alkaline water and are located in a bottle-shaped building (V<0xC3><0xA1>rosi Ter<0xC3><0xB6>m<0xC3><0xA1>l).
Spectacular views, on the other hand, offer many heated outdoor pools in Switzerland and Austria: While you have the whole city in mind from the Zurich rooftop pool, you can look at the snow-covered Arlberg in the outdoor pool of a bath in St. Anton - and: in the steam bath there is a window from which you can observe the movement on the ski slope.
Perhaps the most extraordinary pool design awaits bathing guests in L<0xC3><0xA4>ngenfeld: the Aquadome <0xC3><0x96>tztal looks like a UFO just landed in the Alps.
In winter, three open bowls are used for steaming, while in the background the mountains of the <0xC3><0x96>tztal rise into the sky.
Alhambra in the Black Forest
Not in every swimming pool did the pool collector Meder get the smell of chlorine in his nose.
Many thermal baths smell of sulfur, in the <0xC3><0x81>rp<0xC3><0xA1>d bath in Békescsaba, Hungary, it smells so strongly of heating oil that it is hardly believed to have landed in a health bath.
The smell comes from the alkali-hydrogen carbonated healing water, which is almost black and whose slick sticks to the skin as soon as you slide into the pool - a wellness experience of a special kind.
In one place, however, Iris Meder was also disappointed in her search for beautiful bathing spots: when she wanted to visit the outdoor and sunbathing area in the Czech town of Bad Luhatschowitz, she found a locked area.
The bathroom, designed in 1902 by architect Du<0xC5><0xA1>an Jurkovic, has now been closed.
As Meder glanced through the weathered windows of the red-white-yellow Art Nouveau building, she saw weeds grow between the tiles.
On the other hand, the decay has been counteracted in a magical swimming pool in the Black Forest: the Palais Thermal in Bad Wildbad.
This bathroom already has three phases of construction; you can discover not only neo-Romanesque elements that date back to the time of its construction in 1844, but also a Moorish hall in the Alhambra style, which was added around 1900.
Since its careful modernization in 1995, the Palais Thermal has been the favorite swimming pool of pool connoisseur Iris Meder - and not only because it originally comes from the Black Forest.
“It’s already a feat to merge so many different building styles into such a great unit,” says Meder.
In such a palace, diving in the thermal pool is obviously only a minor matter.
