21er Haus in Vienna
The Relocated Pavilion
By Ingeborg Wiensowski
An architectural history with highs, lows and happy ends: The Austrian World Exhibition Pavilion of Brussels won prizes in 1958, became a museum in Vienna, stood empty and worked.
It will now be reopened as an exhibition hall.
If modern post-war architecture, clear shapes, glass halls, bold swings and new building materials typical of the belief in technical progress are swarming, then the Austrian pavilion of the architect Karl Schwanzer for the Brussels World Exhibition in 1958 is a striking and famous example.
Schwanzer's pavilion was awarded the Grand Prix d'Architecture for its light and floating steel-glass construction.
The building is still regarded as a milestone of contemporary architecture.
He made the architect so famous that he also built the Austrian pavilion at the next world exhibition.
With his legendary BMW four-cylinder house plus bowl-like side building in Munich, he finally became internationally famous in 1973.
Its pavilion, planned as a temporary exhibition building, had been erected after the World Exhibition in the Swiss Garden at the Vienna South Station, rebuilt and opened in 1962 in a museum of the 20th century - the "20er Haus" was called it.
However, the building was not suitable as a spatial and technical museum - no walls for hanging art, no good climate.
Nevertheless, it was used for so long until contemporary art in Vienna got a new house.
Since 2001 the building was empty and came down more and more.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has rebuilt the pavilion, it is now called "21er Haus" and will be used in the future as a museum of contemporary art.
On Tuesday evening, the Belvedere Museum, to which the house belongs, opens the first exhibition there - a stroke of luck in every respect.
Agnes Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian Gallery Belvedere in 2007, has completed the new beginning.
Husslein-Arco, a doctoral art historian with a notable career in the youth as an art runner, later at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and as founding director of the Museum der Moderne Salzburg, strongly implemented the conversion with politicians and monument keepers, she acquired public funds and private traces.
In addition to contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba should be exhibited by the foundation of the same name, there should be a café and a bookstore, and an office building had to be built for this purpose.
Strict supervision, small state
Krischanitz was the ideal cast for the performance.
Not only because he had sensibly rebuilt and expanded Joseph Olbrich's Secession in Vienna and won the competition, but because he studied at Schwanzer at the Technical University of Vienna and the pavilion was an "incredibly important place" for him, where he had "almost every weekend" to look at the exhibitions.
He knew the original design, and he knew the problems of the building, which already lost its generosity and lightness when it was moved to Vienna and its re-use.
There were much bigger problems with the current reconstruction: the building was "an energy sling", says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass facade were replaced, glass fiber reinforced insulating glass was used and the glass roof was replaced with special safety glass.
Cold-bridge steel girders have been reinforced or replaced, and asbestos-filled ceilings have been refurbished.
Two basements provided space for new use, a lowered light trench between house and street provides exposure, a bridge leads to the entrance - almost a new building, but still the light Schwanzer pavilion.
The original exterior doors have remained, the house is painted in the old red-brown rust protection shade.
And the cinema is exactly the same as it used to be.
And all this under the strict supervision of the monument authority and with a small state.
"Often a material had to be found that is good and cheap and also liked the monument protection office," says Krischanitz, pointing to a rocky floor in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and alterations, the building has remained flexible and light.
It has been difficult with the pavilion, "which came from Brussels", Krischanitz recently said, a typical "drop-in-the-city story".
Such an architecture is "always in the wrong place" and still wants to "awaken a real consciousness".
In this case, however, the 21er Haus is not in the wrong place, because it has occurred an urban luck case: around the Swiss garden, the completely newly planned "Main Station Quarter", with office and residential buildings, is being created.
And another good luck case may still occur: the 21st house could get reinforcement from another Krischanitz building, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg has bought the Berlin Temporary Kunsthalle, and as you can hear, she is already negotiating with the city about a neighboring location in the Swiss Garden.
