She had combined the image of the silent and solid Swiss asset manager with ambitious goals: she also wanted to become a very large number in investment banking.
On the one hand, UBS in 2007 managed $1.6 trillion more money from wealthy clients than any other bank in the world.
And on the other hand, as an investment bank, it was promoted to the league of the largest banks in the world.
That made an impression.
The former banker and later long-time banking professor in Zurich, Hans Geiger, says: "I always presented UBS to my students as a model of a good bank at that time."
"From today's point of view, one wonders: how could I be so wrong?"
He was so wrong.
In 2007, it was revealed for the first time that something had gone wrong at UBS.
In the middle of the year, CEO Peter Wuffli resigned surprisingly, who until then was considered a highly intellectual and equally brilliant banker.
A few months later, he knew why he had left.
The bank’s investment arm had been squandered with subprime securities and had to write off billions.
To shoulder this, UBS announced a capital increase in the amount of say and write 13 billion francs.
In fact, she found investors for this, but one that some would have had their noses pierced until recently: an opaque Asian state fund from Singapore and an Arab state fund that was so secretive that you didn’t even know its name.
But that was only the first blow.
In April 2008 it got worse.
The bank had to announce new billion-dollar losses, with Marcel Ospel, chairman of the board of directors, the second-highest-paid board of directors in Switzerland, resigning in 2006.
In October 2008, the disaster followed: the UBS was in the midst of a financial crisis and had to be rescued by the state.
The National Bank bought tens of billions of problematic securities from UBS, while the Swiss Confederation gave six billion Swiss francs for a bond that allowed it to become a co-owner of the bank.
The whole of Switzerland was shaken - because she noticed how dramatic it is for a small country when it hosts such large banks.
After all, the balance sheet total of UBS 2007 was more than five times the economic performance of Switzerland (see graph).
"Once again, we could not save the UBS," says bank researcher Geiger.
The first disaster was followed by the second.
A few months later, the UBS capitulated in the tax dispute with America and declared itself ready to release the data of wealthy customers who may have evaded taxes with the help of the bank.
In addition, she agreed to a payment of $780 million - as a refund of unjustified profits from these transactions, including penalty fees.
Thus, the UBS knew more or less openly to have helped in the tax evasion.
At the same time, she lost something that had always been her capital in the competition for rich customers: the nimbus of silence.
After the scandal, Swiss banking secrecy was no longer the same.
This was followed by the resignation of the CEO and Chairman of the Board of Directors.
And the exodus of customer money.
Within a few months, the bank had lost its credibility in both central business areas: in investment banking through the mis-speculation and in asset management through the help of tax evasion.
And just as it became a little quieter again, just as you thought, now the UBS will get it again, then follows this unfortunate dealer story: A single dealer beckons 1.7 billion euros before the bank realizes that something is wrong.
And it will be obvious: With risk management in investment banking, it obviously still does not work.
"With the case of Adoboli, it has been found that risk control has changed too little," says Martin Janssen, economist and finance professor at the University of Zurich's banking institute.
The chief financial officer of a large German bank is also sure: "The problem with UBS is that it has no control over risk control."
It was precisely the idea of the caution with which the Swiss bankers had long ago taken to become guardians of the great assets of the world: not too great risks, but security for money - even if the world might collapse beyond the Alpine republic.
The vaults of the Swiss banks had become a symbol of unwavering reliability, like Lindt and Spr<0xC3><0xBC>ngli for particularly noble chocolate.
The headquarters of UBS in Zurich still fits the cliché of the well-established Swiss private bank - it is only slightly larger.
