Jewelers such as Tiffany's can be found here between traditional Swiss shops such as the Confiserie Spr<0xC3><0xBC>ngli.
Swiss banks have resided here for centuries: from the National Bank to the Palace of Credit Suisse to elite private banks such as Julius B<0xC3><0xA4>r.
You enter the reception hall of the UBS through a heavy revolving door.
Inside the walls are marble-clad, in front are thick leather armchairs, next to the bank logo a large signpost to the "safe".
UBS knows what the customer is looking for here: Security.
This idea of the Swiss bank has both Swiss large banks, UBS and Credit Suisse, but at some point displaced - or betrayed, as the head of a small Swiss private bank finds.
He prefers not to read his name in the newspaper, after all, like all Swiss bankers, he also does business with the two big banks.
The UBS had become much too big, he finds - especially in investment banking, where the Anglo-Saxons would also have spread.
The Swiss had nothing else to say.
"And if so, they have long adapted to the customs of the Anglo-Saxons."
In fact, it was the Anglo-Saxon investment banking that changed UBS, brought it high profits and then the debacle: No European financial institution has lost as much money in the subprime jungle as the Swiss big bank.
On October 15, 2008, the disaster became visible.
"On that Wednesday, the government coalition of the small seven-million country decided the biggest rescue in the history of their nation," writes author Lukas H<0xC3><0xA4>ss in his book "The UBS Crash".
Up to 68 billion francs, or around 45 billion euros, were approved by politicians to save the large bank from bankruptcy.
How could this happen?
If you talk to Swiss bankers, they see the problem especially in the size of UBS.
In June 1998, two of the three Swiss major banks merged into one giant group.
A bank was created, which was already too big for small Switzerland at the time of the merger - and continued to grow.
It helped that the two different predecessor banks of UBS complemented each other: a rich but sleepy bank with a focus on asset management in Zurich and a poorer but already more internationalized.
Suddenly, the internationalized investment bankers came to a favorable amount of money, with which they could spin a huge wheel.
Two names are associated with this rise of UBS: Peter Wuffli, CEO of UBS from 2001 to 2007, and Marcel Ospel, then Chairman of the Board of Directors.
“I always thought Wuffli and Ospel were a dream team,” says bank researcher Hans Geiger.
"Wuffli, the high-intellectual, the humble, who understands a lot of models and statistics, and Ospel, the belly man, who has worked his way up from banking to the very top."
But Ospel ultimately relied on Wuffli.
And Wuffli probably made a decisive mistake in the end: “He thought his models were the reality,” says Geiger.
“This is a tragic case.”
Tragic, maybe.
It is clear that arrogance came before the fall.
Employees of UBS clearly remember the executive meetings, at which CEO Wuffli repeatedly uttered the same word: Goldman Sachs from the throne.
The American Bank was the most powerful investment bank in the world.
She led the League Tables, the rankings that documented the success of the banks of the time.
