However, corporate consultants who were commissioned highlighted a weakness: In the international interest rate business, in the banking language "Fixed Income", there is a huge gap to the largest banks.
UBS has gaps in U.S. mortgage products.
To close this gap, UBS embarked on an adventure that almost cost her existence.
Hungry for growth, both the bank itself and a hedge fund founded before it invested in American subprime assets.
It developed into a huge machine that packaged and passed on securities on American mortgage loans – but also kept risks to itself.
Even when other banks have been looking for a way out.
“Even in the summer of 2007, when the American real estate market was on fire, UBS bought there,” says bank expert Geiger.
The greater the euphoria, the deeper the case.
One manager after another had to go as the attempts to clean up were more difficult than expected.
Posts at the UBS became the headquarters of the swindlers and are still wobbly.
Whoever runs the big bank now has an almost impossible job.
He needs to find a strategy for a bank that has lost all its obvious business models.
