Peter Englund's new book "Beauty and Horror: A History of the First World War, told in Nineteen Fates" begins with a long list of main characters that goes to one's heart.
Here’s a tip on how to proceed: Carefully cut out this page and make it your bookmark.
You will get to know these people very well in Englund’s novel narrative. And these main characters will function as your GPS, as a lighthouse in these few moments where you, like Englund’s men and women, are lost in the fog of war and deprived of your illusions.
Peter Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which determines the Nobel Prize for Literature.
He has written an unusual book that he does not inappropriately describe as "a work of anti-history."
It contains only a few big names, important contracts or famous battles. There are hardly any ambassadors, furious reporters or discussions about tactics and equipment.
It’s less a book about what happened, he explains, but rather “a book about how it was.” It’s about “feelings, impressions, experiences, and moods.”
"Beauty and Terror" almost brings together the experiences of 20 more or less inconspicuous men and women on both sides of the war, from schoolgirls and botanists to mountaineers, doctors, ambulance drivers and office workers.
Some of these people become heroes.
Some become prisoners of war, lose limbs, go crazy, or die.
Each of these lives flickers up like the votive candles in a church, some come in addition while others go out.
Englund's book differs from the usual history books.
It also corrects the notion that the First World War was only the devastating position war on the Western Front.
"Beauty and Terror" walks with expert views on other war scenes: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
On the soldiers in this book fall bee baskets, one celebrates Christmas among the pyramids in Egypt, Tsetse flies are an insoluble problem.
This is almost from the beginning of a moving book.
The war floods the lives of these people like a natural disaster, like a hurricane Katrina that smells like Kordit.
Imagine you are a woman who is at home with her children and hears cannon fire in the distance. Do you stay or do you take flight?
Who's coming anyway?
Hardly anyone understands what is happening or why this war is being waged at all.
"Missing facts," says Englund, "were furnished with suppositions, assumptions, hopes, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares, and rumors."
"Beauty and Horror" follows individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young German ship sailor.
Their stories were mostly taken from memories, letters, and other previously published material.
Their life stories can be frightening or moving, but they are extremely alive in the depths of the collection of small moments that are lost in detail.
Many of them act out of want and help themselves.
In the story of a German schoolgirl, he tells: "Replacement, everywhere replacement."
"Replacement coffee, wrong aluminum, wrong eraser, paper joints, wooden buttons."
He talks more about food replacements in Germany.
He describes "meat made from pressed rice and baked in hammock fat (and most recently served with a wrong bone made of wood), tobacco made from dried roots and dried potato peels, shoes that were soaked with wood."
There were, as he notes, "837 registered food substitutes allowed in the production of sausages, 511 registered coffee substitutes."
Some stories are about honor and bravery.
An American recognizes his own urge for savagery and says of the war: "You feel that, despite everything, this is what was intended for men rather than to sit in a chair, with the evening paper or the bestseller and a cigarette and a whisky in hand, and to do so as signifying such a fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade of civilization and as if he could not stomble on it."
Conversely, a British soldier realizes that he is likely to die and no one will notice or take care of it.
