Mission Completed, Congress Ready to Agree on Libya
In the end, it looks as if Republicans and Democrats in Washington are already in agreement on the insurgency in Libya.
All that was needed was the success of the revolt, the arrest and murder of long-time dictator Muammar Gaddafi, and the end of American meddling.
On Thursday, the Senate International Relations Committee passed a resolution under the chairmanship of John Kerry (Massachusetts), along with Senator John McCain (Arizona) and Joseph I. Lieberman (Connecticut), praising Libya for the successful rebellion and the U.S. troops for their "courage."
“This resolution honors the brave people of Libya who have started rebuilding their country,” Kerry said.
"It is a confirmation of the support for their democratic efforts by two parties."
The language may sound innocent, but so far nothing has been easy in the Libya debate.
This summer, lawmakers from both parties and the White House argued over the wording of a series of resolutions approving or disapproving the U.S. military’s role in NATO’s Libya mission.
In June, Kerry and McCain introduced a resolution that approved the limited use of U.S. military forces in Libya.
The bill was rejected in the Senate by a broad fringe of both parties and there was no vote.
But on the same day, this law passed in the Senate, and the House passed a decision to cut funding for U.S. operations in Libya.
As a result, the U.S. mission fell into a kind of legislative purgatory – with a Congress that was agitated enough to criticize Obama’s actions as part of the mission, but not angry enough to finally take the floor off his feet.
Then the indecision of the Congress was overtaken by the events.
Tripoli fell to Libyan rebels in August and Gaddafi was killed on October 20.
The NATO mission officially ended on 31 October.
Now the Senate may be ready to act.
The resolution of the Committee on International Relations "congratulates the people of Libya on their enormous courage and extraordinary perseverance in their self-liberation" and "praises the men and women of the US military and their coalition partners who support the military operations to protect the people of Libya for their extraordinary courage and professionalism."
The resolution also reaffirms “the national interests of the United States in the successful and irreversible transition of Libya to democracy.”
Will the new measures receive the full support of the Foreign Relations Committee or will they split the legislature, as the June law did?
The final version comes amid opposition from Senator Richard G. Lugar (Indianapolis), the committee’s top Republican.
Lugar’s spokesman said on Monday that he had not yet seen the final version of the new law.
According to the Capitol, it is up to the Senate to vote this week on a constitutional amendment that calls for a balanced budget, a top priority in almost every congressional legislature of Republicans and some Democrats.
The measures, led by Republican Bob Goodlatte (Virginia), will be the first constitutional amendment to the budget or any other area that currently comes to vote in the Senate or Congress.
Other lawmakers have so far tried unsuccessfully to put their amendments to the vote, although they have often tried enough.
Goodlatt’s amendment is just one of 68 constitutional amendments that have been presented to this Congress and cover a whole range of topics.
Some are double - the same law was submitted to both Congress and the Senate - others only slightly deviate from each other.
There are at least 15 versions of the balancing budget change in the Senate alone and another dozen that would “control federal spending.”
Some of the laws are also identical, but they give their clients — especially beginners at Republicans who want to polish up their resumes — the opportunity to brag about having “written” such a measure.
The Budget Control Act, passed in August, requires both the Senate and Congress to vote on an amendment to the budget balance.
In March, 58 senators voted for a non-binding resolution that supports the idea of such a change.
Beyond the budget, some members want to limit the number of provisions that members of Congress can submit, while Republican José E. Serrano (New York) wants to lift the two-term limit on the president.
Republican Jesse L. Jackson (Illinois) has proposed a number of changes that guarantee, among other things, the right to good education and health care.
A change that prohibits same-sex marriage is, as is a change that prohibits the burning of flags, a recurring pattern.
Some lawmakers also want to allow the repeal of federal laws if two-thirds of states reject them.
As zealously as members propose changes, they move much faster than they have in recent years.
At the 111th Congress, legislators tabled 77 such amendments. at the 110th Congress 66.
The pace is fading compared to that of the early 1990s, when members regularly proposed more than 150 changes every two years, according to the numbers provided by the Senate Library.
But they were not much more successful than today.
The last amendment to be added - the 27th - was ratified in 1992, but was actually proposed to Congress as early as 1789.
