Their strategy: Instead of all the plaintiffs putting their eggs in a basket, they will, if necessary, file many more lawsuits to maintain the pressure.
The defense team for the Department of Defense, led by U.S. Attorney Neil MacBride, has filed a motion to dismiss the lawsuit.
The court’s files, which are available to Newsweek, detail the defense strategy, primarily that the military cannot be charged by current or former soldiers for violations that have occurred in the armed forces.
Due to a 1950 Supreme Court law, the so-called Feres Doctrine, the government is not liable for injuries inflicted on soldiers on active duty.
“The alleged damage occurred during the plaintiffs’ military service,” the document states.
The Department of Defense denies any comment on this story.
Things have changed since the 1950s.
If women are still not admitted to service in combat, the distinction lies only in the name: modern wars rarely have clear fronts.
In both Iraq and Afghanistan, teams of soldiers play increasingly important roles, especially in contact with indigenous women in the war zones.
The result: between these two wars, 150 soldiers died, two-thirds of them in combat.
It’s time to modernize the military, Burke says.
And she is not alone in her struggle: three more lawsuits are pending besides her.
At Yale Law School, the Veterans' Legal Services Clinic is preparing a lawsuit against the four major military academies over alleged promotion of a female-hostile atmosphere.
Independently of this, the non-profit Vietnam Veterans of America is collecting a lawsuit against the military, focusing on the diagnosis of "personality disorder" that victims of rape received to release them from service - a common practice according to activists such as Anu Bhagwati of the Network Women's Right.
Her group filed a lawsuit in December against the Veterans Administration (i.e., the War Veterans Administration), in which she accused her of discriminatory practices in her handling of performance claims for persons who claimed to have been sexually abused in the service.
Nine laws were presented to Congress independently by a mixture of senators and representatives of both parties, providing a number of cues.
In 2010, according to the Sexual Assault Prevention and Response Office (i.e. Office for the Prevention and Reporting of Sexual Abuse), 3,158 sexual abuse cases were reported.
But most abuses are not reported at all, and according to the Pentagon’s own estimate, this number accounts for about 13.5 percent of the estimated 19,000 cases it comes to each year.
The report, which was published in March, also examines the rates of prosecution: in 2010, 20 percent of the cases recorded in the military were brought to court, only half as many as in civil law.
The plaintiffs in Burke’s case describe their attacks as just the first of a series of dreams.
In Lyman’s case, she reported the alleged rape to the military police less than an hour after the assault.
That night, she says, she was asked 11 times to tell the details of her rape to a number of police officers, doctors and commanders.
She had a rape kit and the blood of her attacker, which came from a cut on his arm, was found in her bed.
Six months later, in April 2009, Lyman was heard by a judge, during which she was asked about the sex she had with her boyfriend before the assault.
Six people spoke as character witnesses on behalf of the alleged perpetrator, who was ultimately acquitted.
“I still remember the day the verdict was read,” Lyman says.
"I thought the woes would come. I ran screaming out of the courtroom."
"They took me to the psychiatric ward and I remember when I came out again I said to my commander, 'That wasn't his procedure. That was my procedure.'
Lyman was asked to visit a military psychiatrist who eventually diagnosed a personality disorder and declared her incapacitated.
In January 2010, she was dishonorably discharged, so she received no support whatsoever.
Whether the lawsuit that Lyman and the other plaintiffs have filed is progressing is pure speculation, says John Turley, a professor of law at George Washington University Law School.
However, he notes, "In my opinion, they should move forward."
What stands between them and a verdict is this doctrine that has been criticized since it was first called into question.
I am a critic of the Feres doctrine.
The military lags a decade behind, because they do not have the same incentive and the same deterrence that a liability entails.
He adds, “The odds are against them... but it’s important to them that they try.”
These things will only change if good people are willing to fight.
If the hearing does not follow her path, Burke, the plaintiffs’ attorney, will begin her hundreds of other plaintiffs for future cases.
“We will continue to fight the military in this regard until there are reforms,” she says.
Or until we die, whatever comes first.
Walls Have Eyes: How Researchers Are Watching You on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was just one of many guys who sent their anti-immigration opinion online.
On Monday, Breivik, who confessed to having committed a rampage in Norway in July that killed 77 people, had his first public hearing in court.
Although Breivik may have acted alone, he is by no means alone in cyberspace: he has spent a lot of time before his attack in front of his computer and chatted with some of the millions of nationalists who support far-right groups on social media pages.
After the tragedy this summer, researchers wanted to find out more about these people.
But how do you find them?
This is easy - you just need to log in to Facebook.
“We found that it wasn’t hard to get to them,” says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recently published report by the British think tank DEMOS on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook’s hiding of personal data is so encyclopedic, says Bartlett, that researchers simply need to use the site’s advertising tool to accurately determine their desired demographic data with scientific accuracy — as marketers have done for years.
Bartlett’s team found half a million right-wing groups across Europe and then targeted them with add-ons, but instead of linking to a new band or diet product, the add-ons invited users to a survey asking them about their educational status, their attitudes toward violence, and the assessment of their own future.
Thanks to Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to poll more than 10,000 supporters from 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries – without ever having to leave their offices.
“It’s a fairly new research method,” Bartlett says.
Some of the results are hardly surprising. Online supporters of right-wing extremist groups are mostly young, male, and angry about immigration.
But in a kind of surprising twist, “those who combine their online activism with an offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic, and less violent than those who sit behind their computer screens.”
DEMO’s work is just one example of how Facebook becomes a new hot tool in the hands of scientists.
Idea factories, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study everything from health issues to societal trends such as likes, text messages and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three content per day, Facebook’s “Data Supernova” is generating a research boom that has increased the number of scientific papers with the name of this page in the title by nearly 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is the fact that you can study people through this page that you usually don’t reach with your clipboard on the street.
"If you tried to interview people from the British National Party earlier, it was very difficult to identify them."
“They had to inform the party first, and they would never have given them access,” Bartlett said.
“With Facebook, it all falls away – you go straight to them.”
Others say that the site offers a way to recognize and resolve social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues found that students who discussed their drunk driving on Facebook were significantly more likely to problem-drink than students who remained silent on the subject.
Moreno suggests that peer students, such as residential counselors, monitor the site and help a student if it posts too many status updates.
“You can’t solve a problem if you haven’t recognized it,” said Dimitri Christakis, Moreno’s co-author and head of Child Health, Behavior and Development at Children’s Research Institute in Seattle, Washington.
"We have found a way to identify vulnerable children who would not have been found otherwise."
Facebook is also constantly tapping into its own population data.
The site’s data team has compiled statistics on relationship status and Valentine’s Day, election turnout in the 2010 midterm elections, and a National Happiness Index (primarily using data that only Facebook has access to – digital freedom champions have long known that the site should make its large data repository accessible to others for research purposes.)
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they want it or not. In order to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, the site is allowed to use its own personal data.
But what if Facebook users become part of a survey they don’t even know about?
While researchers have strict guidelines on how to collect their data offline, anything is allowed online.
“I don’t think many users have even thought about the fact that a researcher could study their profiles,” says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, to a 2006 study in which he studied the public pages of students on Facebook.
"As far as she was concerned, it was just about her and her friends."
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that a research participant is absolutely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know how much of the information in a user profile and in posts is true.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things,” says Selwyn.
Therefore, despite his years as a technology researcher, Selwyn thinks that a clipboard and a pen are still the best research tools anyone can use.
“There’s no substitute for going out into the real world and talking to real people,” he says.
"Social research needs to take care of the social - and a lot of social life still takes place offline."
