7 lessons from the interview with the late Steve Jobs, which was shown in a theater this week
After the death of Steve Jobs on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford, highlighting the engineering genius as a great modern inventor.
But what Apple fans may find most revealing in the recently rediscovered Jobs interview, which was dusted this week ahead of special film screenings in key markets, is how much this creative mind has understood business processes and workflows.
He was certainly a designer, a dreamer, and self-appointed hippie, but he was also an meticulous organizer who worked diligently on diagrams—a man who believed that many managers suffer from “a disease of thinking” that “a really great idea makes up 90 percent of the work...[but] there’s a huge amount of ideas between a great one and a great one.”
In 1995, Bob Cringley developed the TV series "Triumph of the Fachidiots" about the breakup of the personal computer. And he sat with jobs for more than an hour, in which they conducted one of the rare, detailed conversations.
By this time, it had been 10 years since Jobs had been pushed out of Apple, and he was already working hard at his new computer company NeXT, looking forward to the widespread adoption of the Internet.
While a small portion of Cringley's interview was used in Fachidiotes, he says that the copy templates of the interview were missing at the time of delivery.
Only after Jobs’ death was a full VHS copy discovered in the director’s garage.
This slightly revised film material forms the basis for the 68-minute film "Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview", which will be screened at the Landmark Theatre this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone who’s known for loathing detailed interviews, Jobs here appears surprisingly eager in explaining his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And incredibly thoughtful.
In the course of the interview, there are four times longer pauses between question and answer - 10 to 15 seconds afterthoughts, in which jobs clearly weighs his thoughts and strives for accuracy.
There are also times when Jobs’ perfectionism comes to light when he seems impatient with Cringely’s questions and prompts him to move more quickly on more important topics or side actions.
Before the era of Pixar, iPod or iPhone recorded, the Lost Interview seems somehow uncannyly far-sighted when evaluating jobs, which other companies do in his opinion right or wrong and represents his own vision for the future of the computer.
It’s one thing to read posthumously about Career Jobs, but seeing jobs here as the aspiring dreamer on the verge of greatness is something completely different, original and inspiring.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
Shortly after he had done all this here, he pulled away and made it.
A quick look at seven remarkable sequences of the Lost Interview:
How he learned to run a business:
"During all the years in business, I always ask, "Why do you do things?". And the answer you always get is, "Oh, that's just how it's done."
No one knows why he does what he does. No one in the business really thinks about things in depth.
That's what I found.
Jobs continues his efforts to streamline accounting at Apple.
Amazed at how costs were recorded—mostly starting with “standard costs” that were quantified to mere conjecture and then adjusted to “deviation”—he developed an automated factory that ensured that business costs could be determined to the smallest extent.
How the Pope was framed:
Jobs talks about the "Blue Box" he built with Steve Wozniak, a device with which one could sneak into the telephone company and conduct long-distance conversations for free.
Much has been written about the device, but Jobs' enthusiasm when he describes the Blue Box as an act of self-empowerment is contagious.
He describes how Wozniak and he would test the box by using a toll-free phone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another as they traverse as many satellites as possible.
“We sent stuff half a dozen times around the globe and when you got on the phone, it came back out in the phone next door a minute later,” Jobs said.
“We were young and we learned that we can build something ourselves that can control trillions of dollars of infrastructure around the world.”
We both didn’t know much, but we were able to build this little thing that can control a gigantic thing, that was an incredible lesson and I don’t think without it Apple would exist.
Jobs goes on to tell of a glorious ploy Wozniak and he had almost pulled when they called the Vatican via the Blue Box in the middle of the night and wanted to talk to the Pope while they were doing the best they could to imitate Henry Kissinger.
Since several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to speak with the American diplomat, the two had to laugh before the pope himself got on the phone.
How he fell in love with technology (and called Bill Hewlett unprepared):
At the age of 12, when he was looking for spare parts to build a frequency counter, he looked for Bill Hewlett in the phone book and called him.
Shortly after her 20-minute phone call, Jobs got a part-time job at Hewlett-Packard for the summer.
"This had a remarkable impact on me, it was the only company I had seen at that age and it shaped my views on what a company was and how well it treated its employees."
Jobs later became one of the HP employees who visited the company’s research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw “the first desktop computer ever made.”
He was as big as a suitcase, had a small screen with a brown tube and I fell in love with him.
I would climb up at HP as a teenager and hang on this machine and write programs for them.
How to improve innovation:
Several times in the interview, Jobs talks about how to spontaneously invent new products.
Early in his career, when he installed some boards, he was asked by a customer to assemble the entire computer.
He worked with a payment deadline of only 30 days and had to think through both the assembly and the delivery of the finished equipment.
Later on at Apple, he recalls the problems he had when developing a computer mouse:
"I remember compelling arguments... They yelled at me that it would take five years [to build a mouse that would cost $300] and I got up, went out and found a manufacturer."
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could build for $15, which was incredibly believable.
About large companies that are slowing down:
Long before he revived Apple, Jobs foresaw the ways in which so many industrial giants got stuck with their visions and lost control of their stocks.
"Let's say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make a better copier or printer, right?"
You own the stock monopoly, so the company is no longer successful.
Sales and marketing make it more successful, so [they are] the kind of people who ultimately run the businesses and the product that pushes people out of decision-making.
The product genius that has led to this monopoly position will be eradicated by the people who have no concept of good products vs. bad products – craftsmanship is necessary.
This happened at Xerox.
Xerox could have owned the entire computer industry.
You could have been ten times bigger if Microsoft had been in the 1990s.
They have won the victory.
About innovation as an art form:
"There's a lot of craftsmanship between a great idea and a great product... when you develop this great idea, it changes and grows."
You learn a lot about its subtleties.
You have to make votes, certain things you can't do, but electrons, glass, robots, factories.
You have to remember 5000 things, these concepts, and bring them all together...
Ultimately, it runs out of taste, it runs out of trying to deal with the best thing that humans have created, and then trying to bring these things together into what you do.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We are always shameless in stealing great ideas.
Part of what made Macintosh great was that the people who worked there were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians who happen to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If it weren’t for the computer industry, they’d be doing fantastic things in other areas.
