A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, who was appointed on Sunday, would meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm the formation of the government.
It is assumed that he will present a cabinet composed mostly of technocrats, although it is not yet clear when the new Prime Minister will take office.
Monti said he would present to the president the results of talks with political parties on government formation.
"I want to reaffirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to cope with these difficult times," the former EU commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly confirm the formation of the government, but his comments show that the obstacles have been overcome.
The “frame is now well laid out,” he added.
Monti has managed to form a government in less than three days, which is much less time than normal, while Italy is fighting a political and financial crisis that has pushed the cost of debt to an unbearable level.
The new government, led by former EU Commissioner Monti, must adopt a tough austerity package demanded by Europoliticians to regain the strained confidence in Italy.
The pressure on Monti in a hurry was further compounded by the fluctuating market situation, which put interest rates on Italian government bonds at 7 per cent for 10 years, in line with the situation in which Greece and Ireland were forced to apply for the European bailout.
Emma Marcegaglia, president of the Italian industrial association Confindustria, told the press after a meeting with Monti: "We said we would support this government by all means."
We believe that this government is the last chance for Italy to emerge from this emergency.
Montis’ chances of success were greatly increased by the support of the PDL party of Silvio Berlusconi, who had to resign on Saturday as a result of the crisis.
“We believe that Professor Monti’s efforts are destined to produce good results,” said Angelino Alfano, secretary of the center-right party.
The support of the PDL, Italy’s largest party, is essential, because so far many of its members have spoken out against a government composed mostly of technocrats, which Monti is currently forming.
Support from Parliament
The new government of Monti needs strong parliamentary support to implement the probably unpopular austerity measures.
Resisting his efforts or delaying the reforms could once again lead to a devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks, with its indication that a failure of Montis is a disaster, also exerts pressure.
On Monday, Monti began his debates with political parties, trade unions and business associations, as well as with youth and women’s organisations.
The session will be closed on Tuesday evening.
Monti was appointed this Sunday by Napolitano, who set in motion an extremely rapid change of government in response to the crisis.
After a short respite towards the end of last week, when it was announced that Berlusconi would step down, as a result of the uncertainty over the new prime minister’s success, the cost of Italian government bonds has again reached critical limits.
A rescue of Italy with a state debt of 1.8 trillion euros would be too much for the current EU bailout.
Monti said his government must last until the next elections, which are expected to be held in 2013, despite predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement the reforms instead of preferring the elections.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the major parties insist that this should consist only of technicians, a reference to their concerns given the procedure imposed by pressure from financial markets.
Political sources point out that mutual distrust and disagreements between the parties complicate the inclusion of people from political life.
