The quintet included Costa Rica in its tour to celebrate its twenty-year existence
"Playing in Costa Rica is a dream come true"
In the exclusive interview with Viva, bassist Jeff Ament of Pearl Jam says the band is ready to give one of their best concerts next Sunday at the National Stadium.
More than 20 years they were expected, but the band assured that a dream would come true for them when they play in Costa Rica.
This was assured by the bassist and co-founder of the group, Jeff Ament, who gave Viva an exclusive interview from Brazil last week.
The band is in the South American part of their tour to celebrate their twenty-year existence and on Sunday, the 20th, they make their only stop in Central America.
On this day, they will perform at the National Stadium from 7.30 p.m. together with the band The X from Los Angeles and Las Robertas from Costa Rica.
You are reading an excerpt from the conversation, the full transcript of which can be found in the online edition of La Naci<0xC3><0xB3>n.
For your Costa Rican fans, a dream comes true when Pearl Jam plays in Costa Rica: Are you aware of what this means for your fans?
Playing in Costa Rica is a dream come true for us.
This is just the second time we’ve played in South and Central America, and so far it’s been great.
I've only been to Costa Rica once, it's such a beautiful country that we're sure to stay there for a few more days.
It is exciting for us to bring our music there.
I ask you this because the fans of the band are completely devoted. They experience the days before the concert intensely.
What do you say to your most enthusiastic fans?
Thank you for being by our side all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica. Thank you for waiting so long and we are sorry for taking so long to get here.
Some people even think that your concert will be the biggest show of the year.
Doesn't that put a bit of pressure on your visit?
Some of the greatest shows we’ve put on in the last 21 years have taken place in the last two weeks.
We played a couple of giant shows in Sao Paulo and we hope they made us fit for this concert in Costa Rica.
We really want to play there.
We love this country, we love to surf and are passionate about the jungle, making Costa Rica one of the best countries in the world.
How did you get to know Costa Rica and its waves for surfing?
Many of our friends are surfers and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo where the waves are simply unimaginable.
My friends have always gone surfing to Costa Rica and Nicaragua. Together with Mexico, these are the excellent areas for surfing. This way, about people who love surfing, we learned about it.
With a look at the tour you have offered huge shows with many songs.
What are your plans for the event in Costa Rica?
Since we’ve never played there, we don’t set any limits.
We will try to give the best possible show with many different songs. We want to play a few songs from each album and offer our fans a good and versatile repertoire.
You never repeat your repertoire.
Why? Why?
I think this is partly because we have nine records and can play over 120 songs. Everyone likes a different song, so the decision we are going to play is not an easy one.
If we record two or three songs that we haven’t played in a long time, we can better maintain our concentration and they surprise us because they remind us of the reasons why we liked these songs, otherwise they might be forgotten.
This makes the show more interesting for us and I think, therefore also for the audience.
With this tour, you celebrate your twenty-year history.
When you look back, do you find it hard to believe in your success?
Yeah, totally.
First of all, I think that none of us imagined ever playing in a great rock band, and that for over 20 years, and that seems like a dream.
We continue to rely on this blessing and find it great to be able to make music together even now.
We like each other and are excited to make music.
We are lucky to be able to drive to the places of the world that we have always wanted to visit.
Things couldn't be better.
What did it mean for you to actively participate in the grunge’s birth?
It has always been an honor to be part of this group of great bands.
We are good friends with the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising and abundantly unusual when a movement emerges from a group of friends.
From time to time, a band emerges from a city, but it is already unusual for five or ten groups to come from the same city at the same time.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle Group.
Sometimes we still play together.
Last year we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and in Canada with Mudhoney and we saw Soundgarden on their tour. We are still happy to be friends with all of them and we are honored to be part of this emerging Seattle sound.
It’s also very unusual that a band like yours has stayed with the same musicians for so long.
Yes, four of us have been playing together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago. That alone is much more time than many bands survive.
First of all, I believe that we all appreciate being alive and that we care about each other.
We are all close friends, which is why musical paths have opened up, giving each individual the freedom to experiment.
One of us trusts the other and his music, and we couldn't be better off.
Your relationship with fame hasn’t always been easy, but thanks to your success, you were always able to do what you wanted.
How do you find a balance?
The way we have grown has made it easier for us to find a balance.
We make sure not to be on tour too often, because it’s too easy to fall for this game with huge crowds who love your music.
As long as you remember that people came because of the music, it reminds you that you have to pay attention to the music and what it has brought to life, without being obsessed with being a famous rock star. That has never interested us anyway.
What memories do you have of your other project Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote very good songs and in the beginning it was great.
We were a band for three years that had never released a record until the death of Andy (Andrew Woods).
We were disappointed to have taken so long. We are still good friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who built the band with us. When I hear a song or see photos, I remember what an incredible person Andy was and how he made me laugh. It was always a joy to talk about music, to work, and to talk about the music.
He was an extraordinary person and we miss him.
The local band Las Robertas are responsible for the opening of the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know their works, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose the band for the opening?
Yes, the production sent us videos from several groups and we liked this band the best. That's why we are curious to see what Las Robertas can offer live. That will certainly be exciting.
Why do you always change the text of Yellow Ledbetter when you play live?
That’s a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), I have no idea.
He sings it, and I think he sings the first thing that comes to his mind.
Who influenced you as a bassist?
of so many+
The first ones I think of include Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk about the bass players I like all afternoon.
How has Pearl Jam managed to keep the grunge alive, even though it is no longer a fashion phenomenon?
I think we all don’t feel very connected to the word grunge.
When I think about it, I think about the bands I mentioned before, such as Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the others that came up at the same time. Even though they are still important today, I think it’s great, because it’s worth listening to this music and bands like Mudhoney are now making better music than ever before.
At first her music was darker, now she is more positive.
Why? Why?
That’s interesting, because I think there are a few songs on the new album that might seem a bit light-hearted, but there are also other songs like The End or Just Breathe that are classified as very dark songs, although they also have something positive in them.
Both of them came to me with tears when I heard Ed play them, they're very dark songs.
I think when you get older and something traumatic has happened in your life – for example, when you lose a family member or a friend – it affects your artistic work and your music and these two songs clearly embody that for me.
But I also believe that you can be a happy person and still make dark music.
