Fujimori returned to hospital for medical examination
Former President Alberto Fujimori was admitted to a public hospital on Tuesday to investigate the muscle loss of his legs, his family doctor informed.
The 72-year-old Fujimori, who served 25 years in prison for human rights violations during his reign (1990-2000), has several ailments, including tongue cancer, which operates four times and is under control.
Alejandro Aguinaga, a congressman and his personal doctor, told TV that Fujimori would be examined for three days at the Peruvian hospital Instituto Nacional de Enfermedades Neopl<0xC3><0xA1>sicas to determine the reason for his pain and muscle loss in the lower body.
Aguinaga commented that, in his opinion, Fujimori could be pardoned for humanitarian reasons, but he did not wish to do so because he considered him innocent.
He was operated on four times for tongue cancer and lost 18 kilos of weight, in addition to other diseases such as severe erosive gastritis, a cyst in the pancreas, kidney stones, high blood pressure and circulatory problems in the legs, the doctor counted.
Fujimori has been in the Direcci<0xC3><0xB3>n Nacional de Operaciones Especiales de la Pol<0xC3><0xAD>cia detention centre since September 2007.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the murder of 25 people by the death squad of the Peruvian army, which was secretly active during his reign.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political relations
An official delegation led by Uruguayan President José Mujica and consisting of several ministers and businessmen will start their visit to Mexico on Tuesday to expand trade between the two countries and discuss political issues in the region.
Mujica will meet next Wednesday with his Mexican counterpart Felipe Calder<0xC3><0xB3>n, which, according to the Uruguayan president, will be the culmination of his booked schedule with politicians, businessmen and a meeting with the collective of Uruguayans living in Mexico.
The meeting of the two presidents in the city of Guadalajara "is suitable for the exchange of information on all policies between the two countries," the South American country's presidential office announced on its website.
According to local media, Mujica is seeking Calder<0xC3><0xB3>n’s support for the incident with France when French Prime Minister Nicolas Sarkozy put the South American country on a list of tax havens at the G20 summit in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude those countries that still act as tax havens from the international community. This statement was rejected by Uruguay and prompted a request to his ambassador in the European country.
Mexico has been chairing the G20 since November, a group of the world’s most powerful emerging and industrialized countries, and since January of this year, there has been an agreement on the exchange of tax information to avoid double taxation with the South American country.
In recent years, the Government of Uruguay has sought to accelerate the concretisation of tax information exchange agreements to remove them from the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) 'grey list', which includes countries that have not introduced all international standards for cooperation in tax matters.
At business level, there has been a free trade agreement between Mexico and Uruguay since 2004, which has contributed to a growing exchange of goods between the two countries.
