Trinijove has helped 6,000 young people threatened by social exclusion
The organization was set up to avoid the marginalization of young people without vocational training.
The first 25 years of life of the social welfare organization Trinijove have led to important results: In this quarter century, 6,000 young people threatened by social exclusion were supported to find a way out of their difficult situation.
In addition, there are more than 100 jobs created for this social group.
On the occasion of the anniversary, an event was held yesterday in the former Fabra i Coats factory buildings, attended by over 300 people.
Trinijove was founded in 1986 in the neighbourhood of Trinitat Vella with the aim of helping young people with low levels of education, without work, with drug problems that were threatened by the risk of marginality.
Yesterday’s celebration in Sant Andreu was attended by numerous managers of institutions and institutions that have worked with the association for these 25 years.
The participation of political representatives of different directions in election campaigns proved the impartiality of the work done by Trinijove.
In addition to the President of the Generalitat (Parliament of the Autonomous Region of Catalonia), Artur Mas, and his predecessor Jordi Pujol took part in the celebrations of the former Socialist Minister of Education Ernest Maragall and the former mayor and currently left-green city councillor Ricard Goma.
The large hall of Fabra i Coats was also visited by the current Catalan Minister of Social Affairs and Family Affairs, Josep Llu<0xC3><0xAD>s Cleries, and the Director General of the Social Work Office of La Caixa, Jaume Lanaspa.
Mas stressed that Trinijove was created in very difficult times and that today’s times are no less complicated, but he added that the work done so far “is a good foundation.”
For the President of the Generalitat, Trinijove is a role model who knows how to fight difficult circumstances and gives hope to people in difficulty.
"The economic crisis is nothing new for the association and the work it does," he said.
Occupied house, in which giant parties were held, was evacuated
The house owners had occupied 11 of the 13 apartments in the building on Balmes Street No. 51 (Barcelona).
The twelve occupants of the house left the building yesterday afternoon without having resisted.
Everything indicates that the nightmares of the neighbors of House No. 51 on Balmes Street have come to an end.
Twelve people voluntarily left the building they had illegally occupied yesterday afternoon, where they had organized huge parties that had driven the neighborhood to desperation. The eviction was carried out on a court order without police intervention.
After the eviction, the door lock was replaced to avoid a similar situation.
"From now on, access will be controlled," the house manager confirmed.
The squatters, who had occupied 11 of the building's 13 apartments - the rest were inhabited - took the entire electrical system and part of the water supply, and they had painted the walls and left all kinds of garbage, especially cans of alcoholic beverages.
On the three lower floors huge parties were celebrated, which lasted up to two days and drove the tenants to despair.
Next to the building is a discotheque, Balmes 51, which also suffered damage from it.
Her owner, Maria Pantinat, told Europa Press that her business had declined by 80% since the start of the house occupation.
The owner of the discotheque pointed out that the housewives made their unfair competition, because they sold the drinks for three euros, while these in the discotheque cost 10 euros.
In addition, the owner of the leisure room had been shown by the neighbors due to disturbance of rest, while according to her statement the noise did not come from the visitors of the disco, but from the house occupants and in particular from the guests of the parties organized there, and which according to the statements of the angry neighbors became more and more prolonged in recent weeks.
The head of the discotheque explained that the harassment had been so great that she agreed with the owner of the building not to pay rent for the last nine months.
The Guardia Urbana (urban police) also confirmed that they have received more complaints from neighbors in recent weeks.
Last week, the chairman of the PP (Partido Popular - People's Party) in the Barcelona City Council, Alberto Fern<0xC3><0xA1>ndez D<0xC3><0xAD>az, had demanded that the building be removed immediately and that the problems of civic coexistence and the downfall of the district be brought under control.
He explained that only one floor of the building had been occupied before the summer, but that in recent months the occupants had penetrated into all the floors of the building and almost all the apartments.
In this sense, he added that "it is necessary to put an end to impunity and to take action against the asocial actions in the building."
Yesterday, another building in the Nou Barris district was evacuated by the Catalan police.
At 3:30 p.m., police approached 35 Montral Street after receiving a call from a neighbor who had been watching four people trying to break into the building.
The four were immediately arrested.
Park or mountain?
Apart from the disputes over the fees, the architects agree to the tender.
The urban tender for the 16 gates reopens the debate on the importance of Collserola in Barcelona.
In the mid-1980s, at the height of the now-defunct Corporaci<0xC3><0xB3>n Metropolitana de Barcelona (CMB), this administration published its mockery on the promotion of Collserola.
The brochure described the mountain as a huge park in Barcelona city.
It was even compared in numbers to New York’s Central Park.
With the demise of the CMB in 1987, the park became, in the eyes of many, the upper border of Barcelona, because the capital of Catalonia is one of the few that does not spread in the north-south direction, but upwards (mountains) and downwards (seas).
The classification of Collserolas as a natural park plays with this idea.
The Central Park was no longer a model, but Yellowstone with wild boars in the role of the yogi bear.
So far, it was when the city issued a huge tender in September, consisting of 16 competitions, for further access gates to Collserola.
Undoubtedly, a gate refers to the concept of a park.
Either this is the case, or someone is planning to set goals for the country.
The question is: Collserola, park or mountain?
The tender is not only from an organizational point of view, but also with a view to reflecting on the city the topic of conversation in the mouth of all architects from Barcelona.
It is almost a recurring theme that two members of this old caste who meet in the elevator can use.
And it is precisely this fact that offers the fabric for one of the rare similarities between what three architects from Barcelona think about it, and some university professors who have applied for the project.
Miguel Rold<0xC3><0xA1>n, Daniel Modol and Marta Bayona: The tender is appropriate.
For Rold<0xC3><0xA1>n "it is necessary" to speak after the attack on the coast about the "front of the mountains", insofar as the discourse of Ildefons Cerda, which is about the green apples, has not been carried out.
“One should assume that Barcelona’s largest park is the beach.
Among other things, because it is easily accessible.
Collserola is more complex,” says the architect, for whom the title “Gates of Collserola” contains a “lexical trap”: one may not “imagine it as accesses to a park, but as a limitation of areas where it is necessary to trade.”
Modol, like Rold<0xC3><0xA1>n and Bayona with urban planning experience, sees the proposal as an "intellectual challenge" that carries "some dangers".
Dangers due to the "uncertainty that comes with the design of a public space today" according to the experiences of the 1980s, which had their "swan song" in the area of the forum.
The first fear is one’s own limitation to what can be built.
“Limiting something always means setting the next step,” i.e. exceeding it.
"You have to think about new urban planning instruments, because the current ones [relating to the Plan General Metropolitano (PGM)] can lead to a real disaster."
Modol, who is closer to the question, says simply that the side of Collserola, which is heading towards Vallesana, "can be understood as a park that is not heading towards Barcelona", for purely topographical reasons.
Modol recalls that there is already a study by the Patronat de Collserola, which should not "fall on deaf ears", although he is grateful to the city administration that it has given its board the opportunity to participate in this project "from the first moment".
In addition, he notes that the proximity of the mountain to the city is the guiding letter that allows architects to participate in the debate, although he expresses his "doubts" about whether this technical profile should guide the established multidisciplinary teams ("exactly the right thing," he says) "We architects should only be a tool."
Bayona suggests that the answer to the question in the title of this article is complex, since in the bidding conditions a global view of Collserola is missing: "There were 16 competitions advertised in cross-section," he says, "on the axis mountain-sea. But there is no longitudinal perspective that looks at the area as a whole."
This, at least in his case, has led him to take part in the 16 competitions.
Otherwise, the program and the definition of a project for a gate would collide with that of the architect of the gate next to it.
In his opinion, the city should absolutely guarantee that the strip directly above the Ronda de Dalt in its entire length is equipped so that a soft transition between the city and green areas is created.
