MSS Announces Research Protocol to Find the Obesity Gene
Mexico’s Social Security Institute is leading a research project to find the gene for obesity in children and adolescents, supported by IPN specialists.
The Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social - IMSS (Mexican Social Insurance Institution) announced that it is conducting a research project to discover the gene for obesity in children and adolescents under the title "Genetics of obesity in childhood and youth", with which the genetic markers are to be found in conjunction with obesity.
Miguel Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez, head of the Unidad de Investigaci<0xC3><0xB3>n Médica en Bioqu<0xC3><0xAD>mica (Department of Medical Research, Focus on Biochemistry) at the Hospital de Especialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI, explained that an interdisciplinary team consisting of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers has been set up.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students at the Instituto Nacional de Salud P<0xC3><0xBA>blica (INSP) and the Centro de Investigaci<0xC3><0xB3>n y de Estudios Avanzados (Cinvestav) of the Instituto Politécnico Nacional (IPN).
The population is invited to participate in the study. Interested people can come to the sports grounds of the IMSS in the Valley of Mexico, where tests are carried out every Saturday from 8.00 a.m. with children and adolescents.
He stressed that the investigation began at the sports ground of Cuauhtémoc (in the west of the state of México) and has continued since October 8 at the sports ground of Nezahualc<0xC3><0xB3>yolt (in the east of the state of México).
When the target of 500 to 600 subjects is reached, the study will continue on the sports field of Independencia (in the south of the capital district) and be completed on that of Morelos (in the north of the capital district).
He explained that the aim of the study was to learn about the factors and the role of genetics in connection with the development of obesity and the identification of risk factors of Mexican children and adolescents for the prevention of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the World Diabetes Day, he stated that it was intended that three thousand children and adolescents aged six to 14 years should complete nutrition-related questionnaires with the consent and under the supervision of their parents.
You will also be asked questions about your physical activity and your family history of disease in order to control risk factors that could result in diabetes or kidney failure.
He further concluded that on the aforementioned Saturdays, the subjects measured (weight, size, waist circumference), controlled their blood pressure and determined blood values such as glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin and genetic factors (attempt to identify genes related to childhood obesity).
