The high calorie intake, that is, an increased consumption of sugary drinks and carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) along with a high fat and protein intake, as well as the genetics to be analyzed in this research project.
Asphalt from the UNAM prevents impact holes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the University of Mexico UNAM, develops polymer-modified asphalts to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
If the signs emanating from the road surface were to be heeded, it would not be necessary to reduce nearly 200,000 impact holes when the rainy season in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (City of the Valley of Mexico) erupts, said Rafael Herrera N<0xC3><0xA1>jera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who was investigating the breach.
In his lecture "Technical Impact Holes", which he gave on the occasion of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible is developing polymer-modified asphalts to produce a mixture similar to asphalt, but which has greater mechanical resistance both at high and at low temperatures.
Herrera N<0xC3><0xA1>jera said that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climates, such as in some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behavior of the road surface and thus avoid the appearance of bumps.
He explained that the asphalt - the heaviest part of the oil - is a hydrocarbon compound, one part of which has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphalts - and the other part a low - the so-called malthenes. Together they give the road surface its characteristic tensile behavior.
The tensile elastic behavior of the asphalt means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180° C., at 120° C. it is very tensile and at 50° C. it becomes almost solid, while it becomes brittle at very low temperatures.
"This means that the resistance of asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes in one day depending on the weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," said the chemical engineer.
The FQ researcher noted that the streets of Mexico City mostly had a flexible road surface composed of six layers of material, the last three of which included asphalt.
Between the top layers was a layer of asphalt, which consisted of small, asphalt-clad and then solidified stones.
Every single stone of this wear layer has been bathed in asphalt.
When the vehicles move on it and forces are generated, this layer allows a good distribution of forces in the road surface.
“If there were modified asphalt, the forces would be even better distributed,” said the chemical engineer.
"A last layer, the so-called support layer, which consists of tiny stones, i.e. sand, which has also been bathed in asphalt, is laid out over the wear layer," he said.
Since these layers are in contact with the vehicle tires, they require a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and they must produce friction.
The one that receives and distributes most of the forces of this road surface, the support layer also needs an appropriate thickness and the material of which it consists must be maintained.
Weather conditions, particularly humidity and temperature fluctuations, are further important factors to consider, especially water, "he said, "because it significantly affects the behavior of the wear layer.
When the terrain gets wet, water penetrates into the layer and only comes out difficult again. This causes a softening of all layers of the road surface and, as a result, the appearance of bumps.
When a punch hole is created, he said, "the cover layer is first removed, while the wear layer is only affected after that. But the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that must be maintained at the first signs by appropriate maintenance programs."
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (National Research System of Mexico) stated that the vehicle load is another important cause of the occurrence of impact holes. Therefore, the thickness of each layer of the road surface must always be in relation to the vehicle load and it must be ensured that this regulation is complied with in order to avoid frequent impact holes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that there was still a lot of research to be done, for example on asphalt emulsions, which are already on the market in other countries, and with which the impact holes could be repaired easily and without the use of high temperatures.
