So was the work of the doctor who identified the body of Alfonso Cano
A Lophoscopist from Cali went down in history as the man who identified "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials plays a key role.
On November 4th, a lophoscopist of the Public Prosecutor’s Investigation Unit (CTI) from Cali came in as the man who confirmed the identity of the leader of the FARC (Forzas Armadas Revolucionarias de Colombia – Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia) by comparing the fingerprints.
Of the seven lophoscopists in the CTI department, Eliazar Gonz<0xC3><0xA1>lez was on standby this week, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been involved in criminal investigation proceedings for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career, Gonz<0xC3><0xA1>lez worked in Choc<0xC3><0xB3> communities, where he often had to go into the jungle for five days to reach the place where the bodies were to be identified.
In 2000, after Valle, he settled over and after completing the required courses, he specialized in lophoscopy, which is the examination of the skin that is exposed to friction, i.e. the palms and feet.
In the week of the match against the so-called Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was told to pack clothes for at least three days.
Something big was waiting for him.
On Friday night, he flew in a helicopter from Palmira to Cauca.
He knew that he had to identify two bodies, and that there was a suspicion that one of the men who had led the world's oldest guerrillas might be one, so he had to take with him the ten-finger print of Guillermo Le<0xC3><0xB3>n S<0xC3><0xA1>enz (his real name).
However, when he reached the place where the body was located with the examiner, he could not identify him because of his physical appearance, because this resembled the images he had seen in the mass media, not in the slightest.
He had no beard, was dressed like a local farmer, wore no glasses, and was much thinner.
But fingerprints don't lie.
Armed with a magnifying glass, ink, a plant cell and a flashlight, Eliazar compared the fingerprints of the body to those on the imprint sheet.
It was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, this man from Puerto Tejada was responsible for informing the Minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinz<0xC3><0xB3>n, that he was indeed the head of the FARC.
In Search of Traces
For a dactyloscope from the Sij<0xC3><0xAD>n in Cali, the appreciation given to President Juan Manuel Santos Eliazar Gonz<0xC3><0xA1>lez at a press conference on the use against "Cano" was very important.
Many people do not know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science with no error rate, which can be a key factor in the resolution of a crime.
Lophoscopists not only identify bodies, they also support investigations into murder and robbery cases and confirm the identity of the arrested persons.
When arrested, many criminals present false identification papers or they have none.
We take their fingerprints and look for them in the database.
The researcher told us that in case of theft, he had to tear a piece of wall from a house, because the thief had supported himself with his hand exactly at this point, when he pulled out a safe full of jewelry and money.
"Walls are difficult because their surfaces are unsuitable for taking fingerprints, but in this case we were able to take the fingerprint of the whole hand and identify the offender who had participated in several thefts," he recalled.
With the help of fingerprints, murder suspects can also be relieved or charged.
Recently, a dead man was found surrounded by bottles of liquor.
In the investigation, it was suspected that a family member could be a suspect, and in fact, a fingerprint on the bottle matched.
Although this does not guarantee that it is the killer, it is connected with the place where the crime was committed.
A CTI dactyloscope explained that "fingerprints with chemical or physical reagents would be taken from the object."
When they appear, a plant cell or a band is used to carry them.
After that, the prints are sent to Asif, which is the criminal database, or to the personnel office.
“The problem is that there are still many Colombians without ID cards,” the CTI expert explained.
He said that not everything is the way it would be portrayed in the TV series SCI.
Just as not everything that glitters is gold, not everything you touch is a fingerprint.
But it can still be used if you make a corresponding comparison.
