Japan is reborn after the earthquake
GDP grows by 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption and ends the spiral of free fall from the beginning of March
Since last March, the Japanese economy has been paralysed, still recovering from the devastating earthquake that led to a nuclear crisis, and the worst disaster Japan has experienced since World War II.
The government’s first estimates in Tokyo estimated the damage to property at $300,000, a blow that seems to be weakening despite the difficult global economic situation.
After three quarters of cases, the data on gross domestic product from July to September helped to finally conclude this chapter: GDP grew by 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and by 6% at the rate calculated for the year.
The value measured in the second quarter - in Japan the fiscal year starts in March 2012 - also means the fastest growth since the period from January to March 2010.
The resurgence can be partly explained by the machine sales for the reconstruction of the areas devastated by the earthquake and the subsequent tsunami.
In fact, companies increased their investments by 1.1% compared to the 0.9% decline for capital investments recorded from January to March, the first decline after six months of unstoppable increases.
Nevertheless, the real upheaval of the Japanese economy is not based solely on Keynesian shocks, which use the crisis to build or rebuild infrastructure.
Japan has woken up especially thanks to the development of domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japanese GDP.
This variable rose by 1%, driven by growing spending on vehicles, travel and leisure activities.
The Stigma of the Yen
Tokyo has entrusted itself to the domestic market after the yen - the Japanese currency - has become one of the "refugee currencies" of investors fleeing the eurozone debt crisis and gloomy forecasts for the U.S., a privilege that loads like a tombstone into the accounts of export companies.
With a harder currency, products abroad are more expensive, a serious problem for a country whose economy is based on the health of major technology producers.
Toyota and Sony, for example, attributed their weak business results from July to September to the yen’s listing.
While markets continue to overwhelm peripheral EU countries, the Yoshihiko Noda government remains vigilant.
“You have to pay attention to the ongoing risks, for example, the deterioration of some foreign economies, the impact of flooding in Thailand and the rapid appreciation of the yen,” said Motohisa Furukawa, Secretary of State for Economic Policy.
The prospects are really not very exciting.
The Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) said most member states had shown clearer signs of slowing economic development in September.
The indicator, which anticipates the turning points of the world economy, revealed that the brakes would be pulled on the biggest economic potentials.
It dropped by four tenths to 100.4 points compared to 100.8 in August.
The euro area is even below this average of 100, after falling by eight tenths to 99.13 points.
