Despite the appointment of new heads of government in Greece and Italy, as well as the best growth figures in France and Germany, the rates of weakened countries continue to rise steadily.
The stock exchanges, which are still concerned about the stability of the euro zone, are drifting even further into negative areas on Tuesday, November 15.
In Paris, the CAC lost 1.4% at 10 a.m. and fell to 3,064 points.
The Dax in Frankfurt decreased by 0.4%, London by 0.1%.
“Due to new tensions over government bond yields in the troubled Eurozone, global equity markets are continuing to release some of their recent gains.
“Capital investors are nervous and only too well aware of the risk of infection,” Terry Pratt, an institutional broker at IG Markets, told Reuters.
The Tokyo Stock Exchange, which in turn suffers from renewed fears from market participants regarding the capacity in Europe that the debt crisis will continue, had closed with a decline of 0.7%.
“Japan, like the rest of the world, has turned its eyes to Europe, and trade is moving on a limited variation corridor as long as investors have no evidence that the situation has stabilized,” said Mitsushige Akino, fund manager at Ichiyoshi Investment Management.
This resurgence of concern about the future of the euro zone is damaging the single currency, which will continue its decline on Tuesday.
The euro has been at its lowest level for a month and a half.
By 10 a.m., the European currency was worth 1.3570 dollars, so it dropped by 0.4%.
According to the stockbrokers, it fell after the CDU, the party of Chancellor Angela Merkel, which had gathered in Congress on Monday, had approved a request that, in particular, provides for the possibility for countries in difficulty to exit the eurozone without leaving the European Union at the same time.
The Italian and Spanish rates are well below the 6% limit.
Loan interest rates in Italy and Spain continue to be at a very worrying level.
This Tuesday morning, the yield of Italian bonds reached 6.85% on 10 years, that of the Spanish stock matured to 6.2%.
These tensions of interest rates in the southern countries, but also in France, continue to fuel the fears of investors.
The future Italian head of government, Mario Monti, demanded more time from the markets to restore the situation in Italy threatened by paralysis due to the debt burden.
The new Greek Prime Minister Lucas Papademos, for his part, had confirmed that the implementation of the decisions taken at the Eurozone summit on 27 October would be "the main task" of his government.
Spain is in the sights of the markets, as parliamentary elections are held in the country on Sunday.
The spread between the German and Spanish 10-year bonds has once again reached a new, historic high.
Expected growth figures for the euro area
Statistically speaking, France recorded an economic growth of 0.4% in the third quarter, slightly better than the expected 0.3%.
However, the Federal Statistical Office INSEE had revised the decline in the figures for the second quarter, with a decrease of 0.1% of gross domestic product (GDP) instead of stagnation.
In fact, it is the fourth quarter that most worries economic experts.
Germany, for its part, had a growth of 0.5% over the same period.
A first euro-area-wide recount is expected at 11 a.m., with the European Commission warning of the risk of another recession.
Energy policy:
Facts should win over dogmas
If there is a topic that cannot be addressed on the basis of short-term considerations or due to emotions, this is certainly energy policy.
The availability and costs of electricity directly affect the purchasing power as well as the competitiveness of companies.
It is reasonable to take an election meeting as an occasion to reflect on this issue as well as on the position of nuclear energy.
The debate will only bear fruit if it probes the totality of the economic, social and environmental consequences of the options proposed.
The French should base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
Although there are 7 billion people on this planet, demographic evolution is pushing for a doubling of electricity demand by 2050, not a huge proportion of the world’s population should have to dispense with a vital element.
At the same time, we must mitigate the scarcity of fossil resources in order to continue to produce electricity on a sustained basis, without forgetting the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions, a theme that has disappeared from the environmental debate, in order to combat climate imbalances.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
Therefore, Germany remains isolated in its decision to give up nuclear power.
This is neither the case in Belgium, which is subject to its decision on the need to find a substitute source, nor in Switzerland, which is currently planning to build only last-generation nuclear power plants.
The United Kingdom, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name a few, continue to pursue their projects with determination.
The United States, for its part, has decided after Fukushima to join another unit in its park by reactivating the plant Three Mile Island, which was shut down after the nuclear accident.
Even if the German model, which is geared towards renewable energy sources, is occasionally set as a model, the reality, however, contradicts the discourse.
The election in Berlin will take the form of an increase in the price of electricity, an increase in energy dependence, in particular on Russia, due to the increased use of imported gas, an increase in CO2 emissions caused by gas and coal-fired power plants.
The totality of these unpleasant effects will already be noticeable within a few months.
The case of Denmark gives cause for reflection.
Denmark is on the one hand a European leader in wind energy, from which it derives 30% of its electricity, on the other hand the country is one of the strongest users of coal and gas, used alternately with wind energy; as a result, its CO2 emissions and its electricity price are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the corresponding European average.
Thanks to the stability of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill in contrast to our French households.
As the energy price plays a key role in competitiveness in the globalised economy as well as a key pillar of industry's stability on national soil, French companies have an advantage due to the cheapest electricity in Europe.
Any significant reduction in nuclear power would therefore entail a sharp increase in the price of energy, which would make the noble statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defense of purchasing power an illusion.
Surveys have shown that this is a price that the vast majority of French people are willing to pay just as little as they show resistance to the principle of this energy source.
Let us remember that our country’s energy policy has made it possible to build an industry with 125.00 direct and 410,000 induced jobs.
Due to its strong export character, it brings a multitude of specialized small and medium-sized companies to the international markets and makes them creators of countless jobs.
Should France decide to withdraw from nuclear power, it would fall victim to a majority of these SMEs, and the annual <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>6 billion in investment goods and nuclear energy exports would shrink more and more.
Which electrician would commission an EPR designed to run for sixty years if its producer’s demise was pre-programmed?
In order to solve the energy equation, one must admit that there is as little of a miracle agent to produce electricity as there is a devil’s work.
The low-carbon solutions developed by Areva for the use of nuclear power and renewable energy testify to the complementarity of energy sources.
Maintaining the highest possible level of safety is an absolute imperative for nuclear power.
In France, we have a security authority that carries out uncompromising and transparent checks in existing works such as the construction in Flamanville.
Their work teams, which have made a name for themselves due to their professionalism, are obsessed with the idea of safety.
Within 50 years, the nuclear industry has experienced three major accidents.
Only one, namely in Three Mile Island, has entered under normal operating conditions; so it went without consequences for humans and the environment.
In Chernobyl, the drama was evoked by reactor construction as well as inexorable human failure.
At Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident was caused by two natural disasters of unprecedented magnitude, which caused the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn as much from this accident as it did from the two previous ones.
As a result of this approach and a cooperation of the security authorities of the French and German operators and designers of nuclear power plants, the EPR presents a draft that allows it to resist such phenomena.
Since it is considered desirable among the electrical engineers to build a nuclear power plant, a construction stop in Flamanville would be a fabulous gift to the competition of Areva and EDF, leaving them free track to seize the leadership position in the inevitable nuclear power development itself.
It is inevitable and legitimate to look for the best energy bouquet for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotions, dogmas and party maneuvers dominate a debate that also determines the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy pursued under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from many angles – overload of police, judicial and administrative bodies due to a policy subject to figures, compatibility of this policy with the status of a "country of human rights", as France had called itself.
Recently, the harassment directed against foreign students from the official side had shaped the weekly shows, the interior minister had casually (see Libération of May 23) announced that France "did not need talents, masons or waiters from abroad".
But this policy has rarely been analyzed from an economic point of view.
There is a broad consensus between the right and the left on this issue.
On the right, the tone was struck by Jacques Chirac, who had declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed, including over 2 million immigrant workers, should not pose a problem for a country", on the left by Michel Rocard, who had stated in 1990 that France "cannot absorb the entire poverty of the world".
The only difference is the degree of roughness.
The fear of invasion of the national soil by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared by both the right and the left in 2005.
From both camps, immigrants were perceived as a burden on the economy and French society.
The only difference is in the degree of rudeness one is willing to admit to immigrants.
Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Hollande restricts himself in his programme to banalities, which point out that partnership development allows us to solve our "migration problems".
This idea of immigration as a burden, as a problem, may have an impact on elections; however, it is economically costly.
As economic experts Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron present us in a recently published work, Einwirtschaftsw<0xC3><0xA4>ndig, summarizing the latest findings on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), a broad consensus exists among the
Restricting immigration would depress growth and damage the labour market situation.
The fears about the influence of migrants are based on the idea that they threaten to replace the domestic workforce, especially the less qualified, by putting pressure on their wages.
Experience shows, however, that immigrants are in fact much more complementary than local wage-earners, since they are mainly engaged in occupations in sectors that are technically unencumbered.
The low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract native wage earners, the more skilled among the immigrants work in dynamic sectors where education is not commensurate with employment.
Positive wage effect
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country where there is a shortage of anaesthetists, this complementarity also has a positive effect on wages and the domestic labour market situation between locals and migrants.
In this way, Giovanni Peri calculated that a 1% increase in the migrant flood would result in an inclusive, long-term increase in real wages between 0.6% and 0.9%.
And this without taking into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants is conducive to the creation of ideas and economic growth (high percentage of immigrants among American Nobel laureates; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants also contribute net to social systems, averaging about 1% of the total budget in European countries.
For example, the World Labor Organization estimates that a person who immigrates to Germany at the age of 30 will contribute to the public budget on average over his or her lifetime a net contribution (income minus expenses) of around 150,000 euros.
At the start of his mandate, Nicolas Sarkozy wished to bring about the missing intersections "with the teeth".
However, these said teeth, which were supposed to deter immigrants, achieved exactly the opposite effect.
Europe invented democracy, now it remains to think through European democracy
Democracy is a valuable commodity; it is also a sensitive commodity.
The European continent should be able to remember for itself who, according to their invention in Athens more than two thousand years ago, had let the tragedies of World War I, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the Gulag, but also Francos in Spain, Salazars in Portugal and the Supreme in Greece pass over.
Some had believed that it was enough to exercise the right to vote, in the most direct way possible, in order to see democracy conquer its enemies once and for all.
It has been known since Napoleon "the little one" that it was a feature of the mental attitude.
The general right to vote, which is a necessary condition for democracy, is not a sufficient condition for this and can just as well become an "instrument of oppression", as the republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot put it at the time.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, separation and control of powers, an education, an education, an economic and social community spirit, a jurisprudence.
The crisis in Europe in which we find ourselves is an economic crisis, but it is just as much and above all a political and democratic crisis.
The change in attitude of the Greek Truth and False Referendum would have had a doubly revealing character in this regard: on the one hand, the need for a powerful return of politics, on the other hand, but also those of the disturbing feeling of their impossibility, their inappropriateness.
This ambivalence should be regarded as outdated.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic struggle have shifted today, and that Republican soldiers, or at least most of them, are no longer aiming in the right direction.
We have nothing to gain by pushing for a success of the national referendum, which has been organised according to needs and in the wrong order.
A free pass for the European sole ruler or a leap with blindfolded eyes into the void of nationalist retreat: a grand choice for the citizen!
No, we want a hacksaw, but a collective task, rightfully so, clarified and steady, an election and democracy, this time at the European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain and Portugal - we do not know where to end the list, by the way - as there is only one crisis, and it is in Europe.
It is the whole of Europe that bows to the dictates of markets and credit rating agencies, which suffers from its powerlessness and its lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that is humiliated at the international level.
One is concerned about the transfer of sovereignty towards Europe - it is the whole of Europe that is gradually losing its sovereignty, and thus every single one of the nations affiliated to it.
The urgency is to return the leadership of the European project to the hands of popular sovereignty.
This is because it is all about whether Europeans can reduce the burden of their debts, free themselves from markets and build a future through investment.
The exit from the crisis has decisions at European level on the condition that they cannot be taken without total democratic legitimacy, without leading us to ruin.
After this proposal has been long fought over by Jacques Delors and the Socialists, today everyone is pushing the European economic leadership to do so.
Agreed.
But to imagine this without political integration and a stronger democracy - as it aspires to the citizens - would be another folly and another dead end.
We must take on a new stage of European construction.
In order to create a republic in France, it was necessary to "create" republicans.
The revolution of interests alone could not do enough here.
This teaching continues to be valid.
We need to build a better integrated Europe at an economic level.
This can only be achieved by creating a politically more democratic Europe, a truly European people's sovereignty.
We need Europeans to create Europe.
"Contactless" chip cards become general goods
The World Fair for Chip Cards opens on Tuesday in Villepinte near Paris in an optimistic attitude.
According to Eurosmart, 2011 should actually end with an 11% increase in worldwide sales of microprocessor chips (EC cards, SIM card phones), with more than 6 billion units sold.
The most load-bearing segment is the contactless technology, which allows payments in public transport or payment of purchases by simply holding the card to a reader.
Compared to the 320 million sold a year earlier, this year 460 million contactless chip cards should be sold worldwide!
Its market share is expected to increase further in 2012 (580 million expected units) and represent over 10% of the global chip card market (6,925 million cards).
Europe is gaining ground in terms of contactless payments, after a long period of lagging behind the Asia-Pacific region.
Some 26 million visa cards are already equipped with this functionality, and 75,000 payment terminals accept these.
In France, the beginnings are rather modest: only 400,000 contactless visa cards have been distributed.
However, consumer markets are making steam.
Carrefour has issued 2.5 million contactless pass MasterCards this year.
In order to move at a higher speed, it is now necessary for banks to equip their customers with these cards.
“Two large French financial institutions have committed to systematically handing out bank cards with contactless chips to their customers in the future,” said Gérard Nébouy, CEO of Visa Europe France.
Banks test payment by mobile phone
However, this is only a first stage on the way to the payment method of the future: the mobile phone.
A vanishingly small percentage of devices have so far been equipped with the NFC (Near Field Communication) technology necessary to carry out these transactions.
"They've fallen into delay".
"But at least next year they should experience a real upward development."
“We expect to sell 80 to 120 million units worldwide in 2012,” explains Marc Bertin, Chairman of Eurosmart.
The banks are taking the initiative.
Crédit Agricole announced yesterday the start of a test run in Caen, which will run from December to next June.
The iPhones of some 200 customers and employees are to be equipped with a capsule that allows contactless payment.
BPCE is running a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
And Société Générale had also announced yesterday that it was preparing the launch of an offer that allows its customers to pay contactless by mobile phone.
The terrorist front, of course, from the Sahara to Nigeria
Paris is concerned about the relationship between al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram sect.
The long-suspicious relationship between the al-Qaeda terrorist group in the Islamic Maghreb (Aqmi) and the Nigerian sect Boko Haram seems to be confirmed.
On Sunday, the Algerian Deputy Foreign Minister Abdelkader Messahel himself confirmed that Algiers has now "acquired certainty" about this.
"The way in which the two organizations operate, as well as the relations between the intelligence services, indicate clear cooperation," he said without going into further details.
Paris seems to be doing a similar analysis.
Investigations into the kidnapping of two Frenchmen in Niger last January have revealed the existence of interfaces.
Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory, kidnapped in a restaurant in Niamey by followers of the Aqmi, were reportedly killed the following day at the same time as several of their kidnappers on the occasion of an operation carried out by the French special forces.
French and Nigerian investigators want to find several phone chips belonging to the terrorists in the rubble at the site of the operation.
Anti-Terrorist
The analysis of the conducted telephone calls leads to several interlocutors who are stationed in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), the investigators are particularly interested in the numbers of two interlocutors: one number leads to a Nigerian man who had been staying for a long time in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria, the cradle of Boko Haram; the other leads to a man who is considered to be close to the Aqmi and the sect.
"This is progress, but there is no doubt that we need to wait for more clear evidence before we can talk about an operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Harem."
“But it is conceivable.”
“It has been known for years that the sect has been receiving financial and intellectual support from Auven and that it is becoming increasingly active,” says Nigerian researcher Kunle Amuwo.
In recent months, these "support services" have become increasingly visible in their course, as have the speeches and modes of operation of Boko Harem, which now indicate the addition of suicide bombers as well as the use of increasingly complex explosives that carry the same handwriting as those used by Aqmi.
The international community, to begin with at Washington, has since then exerted pressure on Abuja to take account of the problems caused by Boko Haram.
The Nigerian authorities have in fact long considered the group to be a community of Illuminati that does not need to be given special attention.
Quick success
Boko Haram, founded in 2002 in Maiduguri near a mosque, a school and the fundamentalist Iman Mohammed Yusuf - which in Haoussa means "Western education is a disgrace" - is pursuing the establishment of an Islamic Emirate in the Muslim north of Nigeria.
In this poor region, the merger is experiencing rapid success.
It politicises itself and demands strict adherence to Sharia law, while its affiliated activists fight against the godless central government.
The activists initially target churches, bars and authorities.
In 2009, Boko Haram activists were particularly active in their increased attacks on the police stations.
However, Abuja’s reaction is as usual indifferent.
The army surrounds the city, there are 800 dead.
Mohammed Yusuf, who was taken into captivity, is killed in prison.
As a result, the sect becomes increasingly radical and leaves its strongholds in the north.
Last Christmas, she confessed to an attack in Jos that claimed 80 lives, then to another in Abuja.
In June, Boko Haram is blamed for a suicide attack that took place in the secure Abuja police headquarters - the first of its kind.
In August, the local seat of the United Nations will become the priority international target.
The formation of a terrorist axis in Africa, which is supposed to lead from Mauritania through Nigeria to Somalia, has since worried all security experts.
While Aqmi has occupied Mali and Niger, the Somalis operating from al-Shabaab in Kenya, Boko Harem appears to be a new threat in the center of the continent.
Last week, Alain Juppé warned President Goodluck Jonathan in Nigeria of Boko Harem and was ready to "communicate all indications".
