Nord Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which runs on the seabed of the Baltic Sea and connects Western Europe directly with Russia, has been put into operation.
It is expected to supply gas for an equivalent of 30 million households.
The Russian gas giant Gazprom wanted to commit this event with brilliance and glory.
More than 500 invited guests, including four heads of state and government, attended the inauguration of the new Nord Stream gas pipeline, which connects Russia and Germany directly below sea level, on Tuesday at the Baltic Sea coast under orchestral sounding and at the gourmet buffet.
German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have symbolically jointly turned the tax on the valve that carries Russian gas into the Western European grid.
With the new gas pipeline, 27.5 billion cubic meters of additional Russian gas per year will be delivered to Western Europe through a first pipeline of 1,224 km long, connecting the St. Petersburg region with Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
A second pipeline, allowing a total supply of 55 billion cubic metres of gas – the equivalent of France’s total consumption – is expected to be completed by the end of 2012.
And the possibility of building a third line on the same track is already being sounded.
For Gazprom, the timely and precise completion of this enormous building looks like a victory.
The project was highly controversial in Poland and the Baltic States.
The Nord-Stream pipeline will enable direct gas supply to Germany, avoiding any route through third countries (Poland or Ukraine) by land.
For this reason, these two countries are losing a little of their power: for them it will now become more difficult to exert pressure on Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
Warsaw, most heavily involved in the debate, was not shy away from comparing the Nord Stream pipeline with a "new German-Soviet pact" in connection with the alliance between Hitler and Stalin for the purpose of occupying Poland in 1939.
This means that the issue is politically extremely sensitive.
Western Europe has gained even greater security of supply through the support of this Russian project.
However, this is at the expense of a de-energisation of European energy, as the project has hit a rift between Western and Eastern Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has succeeded in implementing its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries that have strong gas consumption and whose gas reserves are declining.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us in an organic way," Fillon confirmed at the inauguration of the gas pipeline, pointing out the extent to which the large gas contracts are also important from a political and economic point of view.
All this explains the wide smile of the Gazprom managers represented in Lubmin numerous with regard to the gas supply line.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an outstanding technique.
The underwater line is made of steel with concrete casing, which is supposed to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the seabed, at a depth of about 200 m.
When it was built, it had to be removed from minefields dating back to the Second World War.
"About a hundred mines had to be removed or destroyed for precautionary purposes," said Jens M<0xC3><0xBC>ller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
In addition, reinforced measures to protect the fauna and flora had to be taken.
The line is a long metal line, as heavy as 242 Eiffel Towers, which is not interrupted by anything over the entire length: neither by valves nor maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project managers refrained from doing so, as the Swedes had little desire to see a Russian state-owned company settle permanently at the level of its coasts.
"In the event of a crash, we close the gas passage in less than a minute," said Jens M<0xC3><0xBC>ller.
In the event of a leak, the gas in the gas line thus escapes into the air.
However, this case is considered unlikely by the designers, as the weld seams have been estimated to have a leak resistance of one per 100,000 years.
The state monitoring of the gas pipeline is ensured both by an underwater robot, which is controlled for external observation purposes by a seagoing ship, as well as by a device circulating inside the gas pipeline.
It has the shape of a cigar, with a diameter of one meter, is introduced into the interior of the pipeline and moved through the gas pressure.
After three full days of moving through the line at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device provides the most accurate information on any deformations of the metal upon arrival.
The gas line was designed to operate for fifty years without having to undergo even the slightest repair.
The gas circulation is easily ensured by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the entrance, 100 bar at the exit.
Five companies have joined forces to implement this project.
However, the pipeline remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
Furthermore, the German companies E. ON and BASF are affiliated here (each at 15.5%), as are the Dutch Gasunie and the French company group GDF Suez (each at 9%).
These five companies have formed a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
It is based in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased the entire capacity of its gas transport to this company, on an extendable twenty-year contract.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, no matter how large the amount of gas actually transported is," M<0xC3><0xBC>ller said.
The financing of the gas pipeline construction was secured to 30% of shareholders as well as to 70% by bank loans.
The total labour costs should amount to 7.4 billion euros for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
However, the minority shareholders are anxious to recover their expenses, as Gazprom alone bears the liability risk.
The gas pipeline is located on a sandy, pine-wooded stretch of coast near Lubmin from the Baltic Sea.
The 4.5 meter high valves form the gas outlet gate.
Sensors measure pressure, temperature and other metrics of the incoming gas before it is forwarded to the German gas lines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been supplied with one million cubic meters of Russian gas per hour.
At full capacity, this would be 3 million cubic meters per hour and 6 million in 2012.
Moleskine, a brand notebook.
Created by an Italian company about fifteen years ago, Moleskine now wants to give new style to writing.
It has a flair of adventure, with candlelight hours spent writing.
Moleskine's notebook is easily recognisable, with its black rectangular cover, its rubber band, the eggshell-colored sides, as aged over time.
The Moleskine notebook as we know it today, however, was created in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, which is based in Milan, decided at the time to bring a distinguished design notebook to the market.
Maria Sebregondi, at the time a specialist consultant for the company, is in charge of the market launch of the new product.
The notebook was inspired by a long-established production technique called Mole Skin, which refers to a cotton lacquer used, for example, for upholstery covers.
This type of notebook was in high demand among writers and travelers.
“Moleskine revived an old and almost forgotten object that was considered an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century,” explains Maria Sebregondi, now brand manager at Modo Modo.
Success comes in.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% and established themselves with a sales of 12.7 million units.
This is far from the usual production of the first years, in which only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine crosses the Italian border and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to create a phantom image of the buyers, as the notebook inspires business people as well as students and professionals.
Moleskine has the image of cosmopolitan, cultured and open-minded customers.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees in its beginnings, now employs over 100 employees and has two offices since 2008; one in Milan, the other in New York.
The company sells its notebooks in bookstores, on Internet portals such as Fnac, in small boutiques of the city centers and understands how to enforce its identity.
