Why does the unemployment rate of disabled workers remain at such a high level?
About 19% of disabled people are looking for a job.
Today begins the "15th week of work for the disabled".
Despite a purposeful public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate for people with disabilities is always twice the average: 19% versus 9% unemployment of the total population.
Disheartening?
"No," said <0xC3><0x89>ric Blanchet, Director General of the Association Adapt, which organizes the "Week of Work for the Disabled."
“The progress made in 15 years is significant.”
"At the time, the unemployment rate was not double, but three times as high."
“However, there is still a lot to be done.”
However, it must be said that for disabled unemployed people, numerous obstacles persist before they get a job.
The elderly are more common: 37% are older than 50 years (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% of them do not have a degree and there are only 10,000 disabled people among the 2.3 million students with higher education.
Finally, long-term unemployment is also very widespread: 53% of disabled people compared to 38% on average.
In short, there are so many criteria that make it harder to get back to work and that are the “core of the problem,” says Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, an association founded in 1992 that helps companies recruit disabled workers.
So much for the actual brakes.
Remains the unspoken, the mental attitudes, which certainly, but slowly develop.
A study conducted in April by the association IMS-Entreprendre for the journal La Cité stated that the managers interviewed have "a weak level of knowledge regarding disabled people" who are "overrepresented" by "persons in wheelchairs, mentally or intellectually impaired".
The result is that private companies with more than 20 employees still have a long way to go to achieve the employment target of 6% of disabled workers, which was set out in a 1987 law.
These last-named figures from 2008 refer to a quotient of 2.6%.
“We are now at around 3%,” reports Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the organization that is tasked with collecting contributions from companies that violate this law.
The proof: The number of "fees paying" establishments has decreased as well as the sum of the amounts paid between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which provides for increases in contributions, created a strong pressure on companies," Pierre Blanc said.
"But this improvement also expresses a real knowledge, especially among the large corporate groups."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of the facilities between 20 and 49 employees employ disabled workers, while companies with 100 to 199 employees employ 82%.
